commit_message:
Update commands for removing OSDs

Added OS-specific commands for stopping OSD processes.
Also added commands to remove the OSDs and host from
the CRUSH map.

The nova vmware unit tests are failing after 5/26 when oslo.vmware
0.13.0 was releaed due to change
I34f84f3ea3f5f0d6878f1d4438cf25bf22f293fd which breaks backwards
compatibility by raising a different exception type than before.

The change should have gone through a deprecation cycle before making

There is a revert proposed: I0f8042c6e47f6eb9802e770ffb7d09bdbe57013b

Since this is a library release, we have to block the version so nova
doesn't pick it up and then put out a new release (0.13.1?) with the

Closes-Bug: #1459021

Change-Id: Icf1ce8dbb4b2c0b6b627d5d8be0b85a42e99c784
"}]
commit_message:
Block oslo.vmware 0.13.0 due to a backwards incompatible change

The nova vmware unit tests are failing after 5/26 when oslo.vmware
0.13.0 was releaed due to change
I34f84f3ea3f5f0d6878f1d4438cf25bf22f293fd which breaks backwards
compatibility by raising a different exception type than before.

The change should have gone through a deprecation cycle before making
that a new hard error cutover so clients have time to change.

There is a revert proposed: I0f8042c6e47f6eb9802e770ffb7d09bdbe57013b

Since this is a library release, we have to block the version so nova
doesn't pick it up and then put out a new release (0.13.1?) with the
revert to move forward.

Closes-Bug: #1459021

Change-Id: Icf1ce8dbb4b2c0b6b627d5d8be0b85a42e99c784

commit_message:
Remove some cruft from the service catalog

Remove filtering by arbitrary attr/filter_value combination.
Remove defaulting the service_type to identity.

I expect that more will need to be done to the service catalog before
1.0.

Change-Id: Icc3efeb41ff8c03d1e36e3eca372d2206b6077bf

commit_message:
Pin pyngus version as python-qpid-proton is not in pypi

check-requirements-integration-dsvm is failing with
the following error:

Could not find a version that satisfies the requirement python-qpid-proton<0.10,>=0.9

the latest released version of python-qpid-proton is 0.8.1 at the moment.

Change-Id: I880cffbe003a27e9caba3695e39e39e3bd9b1fcc

commit_message:
Check if the rabbitmqctl command is responding

W/o this fix, rabbitmqctl sometimes may hang failing
many commands. This is a problem as it brings the rabbit node
to unresponsive and broken state. This also may affect
entire cluster operations, for example, when the failed command is
the forget_cluster_node.

The solution is to check for the cases when the command rabbitmqctl
list_channels timed out and killed or termintated with exit codes
137 or 124 and return generic error.
There is also related confusing error message "get_status() returns generic
error" may be logged when the rabbit node is running out of the cluster
and fixed as well.

Closes-bug: #1459173

Change-Id: Ia52fc5f2ab7adb36252a7194f9209ab87ce487de
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Clean up run-tox.sh to make it easier to reuse

This change is the first pass of making run-tox.sh usable by
functional jobs.  It moves potentially optional checks into functions
to make it easier for subsequent changes to be able to conditionally
execute them.

Change-Id: I2b47ad8cfcd7d1a6dd9a86fe8dc8c682c433ab63

commit_message:
changed heat dev docs to comply with conventions

With the incorporation of many projects within OpenStack, it's very important to
use standards in the documentation This is important for formalization as well
as consistency
the proper usage is: heat or Orchestration or Orchestration module
heat should not be capitalized
Openstack should be OpenStack
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/Conventions

Change-Id: I254156ba9bdaa1b754ab21886a23e802755afdb0

commit_message:
changed heat dev docs to comply with conventions

It's very important to use standards in the documentation
This is important for formalization as well as consistency
Per formal doc conventions, the word plugin should not be used.
It should be plug-in with a hyphen service names should not
be capitalized the proper usage is: heat: Orchestration or
Orchestration module. Also made some sentence changes, removed
capitalization from titles per standards
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/Conventions

Change-Id: I6d8f44fcde3ed2ab8ee41e279969f08809ee60cc

commit_message:
Enable use of filter_function in PureISCIDriver

Adding filter_function to capabilities of PureISCIDriver.  Return
total_volumes as well for use with filter_function.

This will open a way for admins to prevent Cinder from scheduling
volumes on a Pure backend once it has reached the array’s limits. The
primary use case for this is volume limits. An example of a
filter_function that will prevent this issue would be:

filter_function="capabilities.total_volumes < 500”

This will prevent any issues with Purity versions that are limited to
500 volumes.

Without that filter_function the scheduler will continue to try and
schedule volume creation if space is available instead of selecting
another backend. The end result would be volume creation fails and the
volume is in an error state even though there are backends available
that could have handled it.

DocImpact: This means the PureISCSIDriver will now respect the
filter_function config option. Special Pure specific fields to filter
off of need to be added to the driver config manual.

Change-Id: I1368b74f79eb8c8560cf86df27f9af9541963a87
Closes-Bug: 1437082
(cherry picked from commit 27a1f66773755456a1bb135a940ba2a835c121a3)

commit_message:
Remove oslo.utils dependency from keystoneauth

The dependency on oslo.utils was due to timeutils. The specific isoformatting
and parsing mostly was to capture errors and/or testing only. This has been
moved into the keystoneauth utils module. The minor duplication of code
is intended to limit the dependencies of keystoneauth library.

Change-Id: Ibe9958a7737dd3dbd1a2cffb984e9d215e8d58c3

commit_message:
Set metadata headers on object create

It's a common swift deployment pattern for an update to be a server-side
object copy, which is quite expensive. Rather than doing a second update
step, just set the headers when we upload the image.

Change-Id: Ic4f5ddddfc403f21eba5972b24a3968ae3ce0a58

commit_message:
consumer connections not closed properly

heartbeat_thread is not set for listeners. when closing connection,
it blindly checks heartbeat_thread and will throw an error causing
connection to remain open. this patch explicitly sets
heartbeat_thread to None.

Change-Id: Ief3bf02f952882ecadf742cdd0bac8edd7812473
Closes-Bug: #1458917

commit_message:
Turn server object to dict so we can pop things

There are consumers out in the wild who are wanting to pass server
objects and not dicts. That's a little sad, but it's easy to deal with.

Change-Id: I6011e9822a52428dbe7d9aaf4d130e655b16253d

commit_message:
Add stack tag filtering options to stack-list

Add four new stack-list options to support filtering by stack tags:
"--tags", "--tags-any", "--not-tags", and "--not-tags-any".

Examples:
  heat stack-list --tags=tag1,tag2
  heat stack-list --tags-any=tag3,tag4
  heat stack-list --not-tags=tag5,tag6
  heat stack-list --not-tags-any=tag7,tag8

blueprint stack-tags

Change-Id: Ib172834f5fc0d60521161c82d0c4793e920646de

@Tim, the change and tests looks good, but since it is a behavior change it would be nice to add a comment about it in the commit message, just so we understand the in the future. How has the use case changed? weren't the etags and size a way to enforce the correct segments were being used?

Also, it would be nice to see some functional tests.

Overall I think this will be handy for slo+obj. versioning since users will be able to just update/revert versions of a segment without having to worry about sending a new manifest."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-05-20 16:43:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Change looks good, but needs docs. At the top of slo.py is a giant docstring that's the closest thing we have to proper documentation; that's probably where the updates need to go.

You should also mention that this only affects initial manifest creation, not validation at GET-time. If I'm reading this code correctly, you can't change a segment without uploading a new manifest. (If not, then there are bigger problems, like Range requests being completely broken if you change a segment's size.)"}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2015-05-20 21:23:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2015-05-20 21:25:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Thiago, added a functional test. Sam is right that this only affects initial manifest creation; we will still verify that the segments haven't changed on download. This was something that came up last night while Sam and I were talking to some Cloud-A guys last night; I ought to find them and refresh my memory about why *exactly* they felt this would be useful, but I think this was close-ish:

Suppose you're doing some log rotation, and at the end of some period (say, a month), you want to create an SLO to provide an easy one-request method to download all the logs for that period. Since the segment PUTs are smeared out in the time domain, it's not really practical (or at any rate, desirable) to track the response from each PUT (which is the documented way to establish etag and size_bytes). I hear you say, "Well, why not just do a container listing (probably with a prefix-param) and put the result?" First, we're left trusting Swift's consistency anyway; there's no real benefit to the extra request. Second, you'll have to translate the manifest keys (hash -> etag, size -> size_bytes). Third, you may need to reorder the segments if you didn't give yourself proper sequence-number padding, as log-9.txt will sort after log-10.txt.

@Sam, added docs. Clarified that this preserves download validation in both the docs and commit message.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-05-20 21:33:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

Seems sane. I'll go try it out and see what happens.

Also, could you put "DocImpact" on its own line in the commit message? That'll trigger a ticket creation for the docs team when the patch lands.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-20 22:02:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Allow SLO PUTs to forgo per-segment integrity checks

While manifests still require 'etag' and 'size_bytes' fields for each
segment (to catch user errors like 'etaf' or 'size_btyes'), an explicit
null for either will skip that particular integrity check and instead
use whatever value is retrieved when HEADing the segment. So, if a user
uploads a manifest like:

    [{"path": "/con/obj_seg_1", "etag": null, "size_bytes": 1048576},
     {"path": "/con/obj_seg_2", "etag": "etag2", "size_bytes": null},
     {"path": "/con/obj_seg_3", "etag": null, "size_bytes": null}]

then the etag will only be verified for the /con/obj_seg_2 segment,
and the segment size will only be verified for the /con/obj_seg_1
segment. However, the manifest that's ultimately stored (and can be
retrieved with a ?multipart-manifest=get query-string) will still look
like:

    [{"name": "/con/obj_seg_1", "hash": "etag1", "bytes": 1048576, ...},
     {"name": "/con/obj_seg_2", "hash": "etag2", "bytes": 1048576, ...},
     {"name": "/con/obj_seg_3", "hash": "etag3", "bytes": 1234, ...}]

This allows the middleware to continue performing integrity checks on
object GET.

Change-Id: I2c4e585221387dd02a8679a50398d6b614407b12
DocImpact

[{'created': '2015-05-27 07:42:54.000000000', 'message': 'Set int-br fail mode to "standalone"

If  the  value  is  standalone, or if neither of these settings is set,
ovs-vswitchd will take over responsibility for setting up flows when no
message has been received from the controller for three times the inactivity
probe interval.  In this mode, ovs-vswitchd causes the  datapath
to act like an ordinary MAC-learning switch.  ovs-vswitchd will continue
to retry connecting to the controller in the background and, when
the connection succeeds, it discontinues its standalone behavior.

If this option is set to secure, ovs-vswitchd will not set up flows on
its own when the controller connection fails.

Change-Id: I2aa959c39f9923883bc2000d9cd09ae2ec294b14
'}]
commit_message:
Set int-br fail mode to "standalone"

If  the  value  is  standalone, or if neither of these settings is set,
ovs-vswitchd will take over responsibility for setting up flows when no
message has been received from the controller for three times the inactivity
probe interval.  In this mode, ovs-vswitchd causes the  datapath
to act like an ordinary MAC-learning switch.  ovs-vswitchd will continue
to retry connecting to the controller in the background and, when
the connection succeeds, it discontinues its standalone behavior.

If this option is set to secure, ovs-vswitchd will not set up flows on
its own when the controller connection fails.

Change-Id: I2aa959c39f9923883bc2000d9cd09ae2ec294b14

commit_message:
Kazoo 2.1 has a bug which is breaking tooz gate

This bug is opened at https://github.com/python-zk/kazoo/issues/315

The PR fix is at https://github.com/python-zk/kazoo/pull/316

Until that merges and is released reduce the required version to a
known set that is known to work (vs one that is not).

Change-Id: I4e2190434247f428ceb7482df7e9c7222ed9c4dc

commit_message:
Remove appliance's hard-coded password in favor of ssh pub key

This removes the hard-coded password from the appliance VM's user-data
and replaces it with a SSH public key, which is read from a file whos
path is configured in rug.ini.

It also disables password logins for the user.  Another patch to
akanda-appliance-builder will allow developers to include a specified
debug user to allow debugging in dev environments.

Change-Id: I7db92bc7fd3743d89d73ab2a0b8da14685c30c69

commit_message:
Add more users/roles to secret/container RBAC tests

Completed the set of RBAC users by adding audit and
creator users for group b, then add those users to the
tests for secret and container GET tests.  This completes
the matrix of tests for secret and container GET.

Updated the scripts to ensure the users get setup
correctly in devstack and via keystone_data.sh.

Change-Id: Ib598cab8c36728f8ad91c940680e0cdfcfca5c2e

I noticed this was taking an argument but not dealing with it.  In
general the functions were undocumented, so I added some terse usage.

Also, the intent of the test-case was to expand the values before

variable.

Change-Id: Ib317ad1e9dd2a5d2232b9c64541fe4a601a2b8da
'}]
commit_message:
Fix msg argument to assert_equal

I noticed this was taking an argument but not dealing with it.  In
general the functions were undocumented, so I added some terse usage.

Also, the intent of the test-case was to expand the values before
using them as the message; make sure this happens by using a temp
variable.

Change-Id: Ib317ad1e9dd2a5d2232b9c64541fe4a601a2b8da

commit_message:
backend_argument should be marked secret

Since the backend_argument can potentially contain a password,
it should be marked secret to avoid leakage into the logs.

Closes-Bug: #1443598

(cherry picked from commit f9db1a65bd4d83d12c572ba4d5807845996ef410)

subject: Replace StringIO.StringIO with six.BytesIO
messages: [{'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-05-27 15:32:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-05-27 15:33:51.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned\n\nooops, i didn't want to publish this work in progress, sorry."}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-27 15:32:45.000000000', 'message': "Replace StringIO.StringIO with six.BytesIO

* Replace 'import StringIO' + StringIO.StringIO with six.BytesIO or
  six.StringIO
* Replace 'from StringIO import StringIO'
  with 'from six import StringIO'

Use BytesIO (bytes) for:

* compute MD5 checksum
* file
* WSGI input, output and errors
* sender response for ssync sender and ssync receiver tests
* HTTP content in direct client tests

Use StringIO (unicode) for:

* mocking stdout and stderr
* inject config into a configuration parser

When BytesIO is used, mark strings with the b'...' prefix to convert
them to bytes strings on Python 3.

test/unit/common/middleware/test_formpost.py: encode WSGI input to UTF-8
on Python 3.

Initial patch generated by the cstring and stringio operations of the
sixer tool:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Change-Id: I9b8367dcee7b9d6aebaa294c7fae61b5fadd402a
"}]
commit_message:
Replace StringIO.StringIO with six.BytesIO

* Replace 'import StringIO' + StringIO.StringIO with six.BytesIO or
  six.StringIO
* Replace 'from StringIO import StringIO'
  with 'from six import StringIO'

Use BytesIO (bytes) for:

* compute MD5 checksum
* file
* WSGI input, output and errors
* sender response for ssync sender and ssync receiver tests
* HTTP content in direct client tests

Use StringIO (unicode) for:

* mocking stdout and stderr
* inject config into a configuration parser

When BytesIO is used, mark strings with the b'...' prefix to convert
them to bytes strings on Python 3.

test/unit/common/middleware/test_formpost.py: encode WSGI input to UTF-8
on Python 3.

Initial patch generated by the cstring and stringio operations of the
sixer tool:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Change-Id: I9b8367dcee7b9d6aebaa294c7fae61b5fadd402a

commit_message:
Support removal of last_activity session flag

This is a simple change that will support removal of the last activiy
session field within the horizon middleware.  Whith this change, a bunch
of horizon code can be removed.

Change-Id: Ia1c9f116ce731b80fb66a191d937a5ef509c81e9
Partialy-Closes: #1450914

commit_message:
Migrate to oslo.context

This removes akanda.rug's usage of openstack.common.context
and instead uses the equivalent oslo_context.context.

Note the old module is still left in place as its used by other old
oslo-incubator things.

Change-Id: I3343106d4da59dede7ca32e66c8ec7ed1abb4ebb

commit_message:
Rename cloud to profile

The cloud parameter was confusing people, especially since it was
inside of a dict that was named "clouds". profile was suggested as less
confusing, which seems fine.

Continue processing cloud as a parameter so that we don't break
anyway, but change the docs to only mention profile.

Change-Id: Idf3d089703985ecc60f23a3c780ddcab914aa678

commit_message:
TOSCA: interfaces for relationship templates

TOSCA relationship interfaces are provided for various configurations to run
on the host or target machine for pre, post configuration operations. Make
such interfaces available via relationship templates.

Change-Id: I6626e5baaa0ebc369d8e4ab74720e880d52926a7

commit_message:
Update get_ports_from_devices for liberty

The API here changed in liberty as of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/173320/
This updates call signature accordingly and allows the ML2 plugin to function
ontop of liberty / trunk neutron.

Change-Id: I21cb6da6aeeb6fcf55a81cd07c4ca88a6285e682

Don't pass None as the cloud name

None.

commit_message:
Fix directory creation on running make with docker target

On running "make docker" we have other targets
workflow then on "make iso", so for building target
$(ISOROOT)/openstack_version we must be sure that $(ISOROOT)
directory exists.

Closes-bug: #1457435
Change-Id: Ifa0ca2f81074d1be040cebb99f3632bcc7270dd9

There is too much round discussion on if we should make 'port-sec' as a default extension driver, and should we leave a choice to user to make extension driver empty, without 'port-sec'.

IMHO, ':-' would be OK, just like the other config item. If we leave a chance of using empty extension driver, the db schema of the network/port created could not be updated if the user manually add 'port-sec' some day later.

@rkukura what's your opinion?"}, {'account_id': 11114, 'date': '2015-04-29 06:35:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

just have a idea that we also need add more logic to avoid the agent use linuxbridge mech when configured port-sec, cause port-sec only be implemented in OVS.'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2015-04-29 14:36:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

In my opinion, devstack should configure the port-security extension by default. This will help expose any bugs in the extension itself or in ML2's extension driver framework, and will make  the functionality more readily available (and discoverable) to anyone using devstack. The goal of devstack is not to provide a finely tuned configuration for deployments, so I don't think any overhead this extension might add is an issue."}, {'account_id': 11114, 'date': '2015-04-30 17:02:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Thanks rkukura for your advice. And the dispute is mostly on using ":=" or "-" to specify the default driver. commit_message:
add the port_sec as default neutron/ml2 extension driver

Neutron ML2 plugin introduces the first extension driver port_security, this
patch add it to be a default extension driver as a example. And also, if not
set it by default, networks like public/private which are created after the
neutron-db-manage's update, will not include the port-sec value.

Change-Id: I3035317c83d22804855517434bd8578719ce0436
Partially Implements: blueprint ml2-ovs-portsecurity

commit_message:
corrected typos throughout murano source articles

suported should be supported
specfying should be specifying
registered should be registered
arhive should be archive
environmet should be environment
removed title capitals where not required
splitted is not a word changed to split
pakcage should be package
scenarious should be scenarios

Change-Id: Idc0b6c4f6043366e7bb95bb57b88fa7e6d304001

commit_message:
Add support for 'boolean' HOT parameter

The HOT-to-MuranoPL converter did not support 'boolean' type as Heat
Template input parameter. This lead to a
400 'Unsupported parameter type boolean', during package uploads.

This patch adds support for boolean type, adds .bool() to boolean field
contracts and adds 'boolean' UI type during UI translation.

Change-Id: I960473916e70f9e17e5b5b1c228b7efd1deb98b5
Closes-Bug: #1450536

commit_message:
remove allow_logical_names check

For now we have not support microversion yet, but allow_logical_names
checkes the microversion.

This logic can be implemented after microversion is there.

Change-Id: Ie1f379f79cb94753767fcb0a2a3e31d5a135d0e9
Co-Authored-By: ShaoHe Feng <shaohe.feng@intel.com>

Hopefully Simon will respond that it's fine to use this in this situation, until then I'd like to wait on this change."}, {'account_id': 161, 'date': '2015-02-02 20:45:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I like the simplicity of this solution much better, but I'm concerned about the scenario where you have multiple DHCP agents/servers per tenant network, all of which are being told to assume they're authoritative for any request they get.

From the config file/manual:

# Set the DHCP server to authoritative mode. In this mode it will barge in
# and take over the lease for any client which broadcasts on the network,
# whether it has a record of the lease or not. This avoids long timeouts
# when a machine wakes up on a new network. DO NOT enable this if there's
# the slighest chance that you might end up accidentally configuring a DHCP
# server for your campus/company accidentally. The ISC server uses
# the same option, and this URL provides more information:
# http://www.isc.org/index.pl?/sw/dhcp/authoritative.php
#dhcp-authoritative

"barge in and take over" makes me hesitant when there's more than one on a network. I suppose there's there argument that is what happens today during a DHCPDISCOVER, and a DHCPRENEW is only unicast (so this would just force the dnsmasq process to say "OK, cool, I'm your guy now).

Either way, will be curious to hear what Simon has to say, but I do prefer this method if possible.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-02-02 21:28:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Based on my understanding of the description of dhcp authoritative for the ISC DHCP server[1] (which dnsmasq.conf says the option is modeled after), it would do the opposite of what we wanted here. Quote that sounds like an issue: 

"Thus if a client requests a lease for an address for which the server is authoritative yet the server has no record of it, the server will respond with DHCPNAK indicating that the client should no longer use the address. "

That sounds to me like it would exhibit the behavior we are seeing now. So either I am misunderstanding that, dnsmasq didn't implement the same behavior like the conf implied, or this fix won't help.


1. http://www.ipamworldwide.com/server-configuration-parameters.html'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-02-02 22:53:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

My email to the dnsmasq list starts here, http://lists.thekelleys.org.uk/pipermail/dnsmasq-discuss/2015q1/009171.html but basically --dhcp-authoritative does seem to work.

Before:

DHCPREQUEST(tap133cc7b7-4d) 10.0.0.4 fa:16:3e:6f:18:5c
DHCPNAK(tap133cc7b7-4d) 10.0.0.4 fa:16:3e:6f:18:5c lease not found
DHCPDISCOVER(tap133cc7b7-4d) fa:16:3e:6f:18:5c
DHCPOFFER(tap133cc7b7-4d) 10.0.0.4 fa:16:3e:6f:18:5c
DHCPREQUEST(tap133cc7b7-4d) 10.0.0.4 fa:16:3e:6f:18:5c
DHCPACK(tap133cc7b7-4d) 10.0.0.4 fa:16:3e:6f:18:5c host-10-0-0-4

After:

DHCPREQUEST(tap133cc7b7-4d) 10.0.0.4 fa:16:3e:6f:18:5c
DHCPACK(tap133cc7b7-4d) 10.0.0.4 fa:16:3e:6f:18:5c host-10-0-0-4

That was in a config with a single DHCP agent running, Simon did mention to make sure things worked OK with multiple to see what happened in the case of the initial broadcast packet being received by both dnsmasq processes.  Does anyone have devstack running multi-node right now to test that?'}, {'account_id': 11762, 'date': '2015-02-03 05:09:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Pass '--dhcp-authoritative' option to dnsmasq

When dnsmasq is restarted, it forgets about all leases (since it runs
with leasefile-ro option). When client tries to renew its lease, dnsmasq
sends DHCPNAK reply with message "lease not found". Then client shuts
down the network and re-request lease from DHCP server (and gets exactly
same IP address). There's a small network downtime which affects
services, like zookeeper, running in VMs.

Change-Id: Ieff0236670c1403b5d79ad8e50d7574c1b694e34
Closes-Bug: #1345947

subject: Pass '--dhcp-authoritative' option to dnsmasq

with leasefile-ro option). When client tries to renew its lease, dnsmasq

commit_message:
Pass '--dhcp-authoritative' option to dnsmasq

When dnsmasq is restarted, it forgets about all leases (since it runs
with leasefile-ro option). When client tries to renew its lease, dnsmasq
sends DHCPNAK reply with message "lease not found". Then client shuts
down the network and re-request lease from DHCP server (and gets exactly
same IP address). There's a small network downtime which affects
services, like zookeeper, running in VMs.

Change-Id: Ieff0236670c1403b5d79ad8e50d7574c1b694e34
Closes-Bug: #1345947
Co-Authored-By: Kevin Bringard <kevinbri@cisco.com>
(cherry picked from commit 74a16fde1c9972dc3c5d07215ca9d5e8f2e23d70)

commit_message:
Improve shell task error message

The shell command which has failed is included in the
error message along with the task timeout.

Change-Id: I0ea474a899ba86d32b6b4f1a96de4baee17ecdc6
Related-bug: #1435603

commit_message:
Clean up the image functional test

1. Move setup_docker.sh to tools directory

2. Make a setup_gate.sh that installs necessary packages including
   docker and starts docker.

3. Add logging output.

4. Add default test timeout of 2 hours.

5. Add user to the docker group before running test cases.

6. Run image build as dockerroot group.

This patch has to be one commit to fix the gate in one go.

Co-Authored-By: Steven Dake <stdake@cisco.com>

Change-Id: I83f3cdb1dabf0dfface589c581cb22c155467acc

commit_message:
Disk Driver: instance_disk_iter

Add a method to the disk.driver API which can find the backing (usually
boot) disk associated with an instance.

This is in anticipation of the snapshot functionality, which will need
to find an instance's disk in order to map it to the management
partition.

Change-Id: I7b200fb20481c69c3cb2d5eb96a6ab1596b8ef2b

commit_message:
Consistent opt args and variable to dentify that same opt arg

The freezerc was using an inconsistent naming convenstion
between option arguments and variable to the same opt argument

i.e,:
--path-to-backup -> (backup_opt_dict.src_file)

Change-Id: I6e70e60797742054e0e5e10b7b2398bc42354e3b
Implements: blueprint consistent-args

commit_message:
Stop running non-voting docker job on nova

nova-docker has been broken for a while and no one is maintaining it,
so stop running it on nova repo. When this is working again we can bring
it back etc.

Change-Id: I63d0b7fe37b92aa807499ee2c7971d47ee86b420

commit_message:
Rename brbm.xml template to net.xml

The brbm.xml template is not used for multiple networks.
Additionally libvirt calls these net (or networks) so
renaming the template makes it less confusing.

Using a more explicit %NETWORK_NAME% tag in the template so
that it is more clear what is being replaced by a variable.

Change-Id: I066a5d0022871804479c1ee325881381b08020c6

commit_message:
Make sure the converted image is imported

Turns out the converted image is being completely ignored. This is
because the `file_path` provided by the ImportToFS task cannot be
overriden by other tasks. In order to fix this, I've dropped all the
extra suffixes that we've been using in favor of working on the actual
`file_path` directly.

Resolves: rhbz#1065603
Upstream-Closes-bug: #1452750
Upstream-Change-Id: Ifbd2308057f33c1f712fa06f9bb3e57f90068fdc
Upstream-Cherry-Pick: d77fd685ea4d552eb4cf6c5c4a1049ed7964ff05

(cherry picked from commit 724f17ac065652bdcf42379f55da3f903ad18f37)

commit_message:
Save image data after setting the data

The image's locations are missing when image's are imported using tasks
because the ImportToStore task is not saving the image metadata after
the import. This patch fixes that.

Resolves: rhbz#1065603
Upstream-Closes-bug: #1453068
Upstream-Change-Id: I43dec450d5fc4bee2131d78dbe3c2b2373c3f739

(cherry picked from commit 8b8384d65c4ea090dc0d04c5bb3a283debc00cde)

commit_message:
Refactor processing reply in ReplyWaiter

At the moment for each msg_id we receive two amqp message - first one
with the payload, a second one to ensure the other have finish to send
the payload. This was made, because a long time ago 'reply' allowed
generator as payload to send multiple messages on one 'rpc.call' - [1]

It's a bad idea - to double RPC messages for each call, so we are going
to remove this the second AMQP message sending. This patch allows
receiver side to proceed correctly old case - two AMQP messages (first
with data and second with 'ending' parameter) same as the new one (a
single message with data 'ending' parameter)

Blueprint: remove-double-reply

[1] - https://github.com/openstack/oslo-incubator/blob/stable/icehouse/openstack/common/rpc/amqp.py#L464

Change-Id: Ic09fe619694c300c4502acb7157d7ecdd47c5fd7

commit_message:
fixup!Patch of "parse_content_disposition" method to meet RFC2183

The spec of Content-Disposition does not require a space character after
comma: http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2183.txt

Change-Id: Iff438dc36ce78c6a79bb66ab3d889a8dae7c0e1f
Closes-Bug: #1458497

[{'created': '2015-04-29 15:33:12.000000000', 'message': '[Context] [WIP] Add context for fuelclient.

Note:
  This patch requires discussion.

Changes:
  New context `fuel' registers fuelclient in osclients.
  This is not done by extending osclient.Clients in regular way,
  because fuelclient setup works different - it actually does not
  need endpoint, in opposite to other clients.
  It requires Fuel master node address, and (optionally)
  its TCP port.

Task input file example:
  {
      "FooScenario.foo_benchmark": [
          {
              "runner": {
                  "type": "constant",
                  "times": 2,
                  "concurrency": 2
              },
              "context": {
                  "fuel": {
                      "server_address": "10.20.0.2"
                  }
              }
          }
      ]
  }

TODO:

  * unit tests

Change-Id: I967dc258a0fbccf750bec48e56b20d4b67a1764f

'}, {'created': '2015-04-30 11:47:06.000000000', 'message': '[Context][Fuel] (WIP) Add context for fuelclient

Note:
  This patch requires discussion.

Changes:
  New context `fuel' registers fuelclient in osclients.
  This is not done by extending osclients.Clients in regular way,
  because fuelclient setup works different - it actually does not
  need endpoint from deployment and deployment at all, in
  opposite to other clients.
  But it requires Fuel master access parameters (address, port,
  username and password).

Task input file example:
  {
      "FooScenario.foo_benchmark": [
          {
              "runner": {
                  "type": "constant",
                  "times": 2,
                  "concurrency": 2
              },
              "context": {
                  "fuel": {
                      "host": "10.20.0.2",
                      "port": "8000",
                      "username: "admin",
                      "password": "secret"
                  }
              }
          }
      ]
  }

TODO:

  * unit tests

Change-Id: I967dc258a0fbccf750bec48e56b20d4b67a1764f

[{'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-04-18 00:06:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-04-18 00:18:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I'm not really sure if this is RC2 material.  On one hand - these are both bugs and absolutely need to be fixed.  OTOH, "improving error handling under failure while recovering from failure" seems exactly like the sort of stuff you'd expect to have to get done *during* the beta - maybe not before?

Either way - here it is.

It might also be worth nothing, even without the timestamp fixes in place, that a fragment index "swap" (i.e. node_index 3 has frag_index 4 and node_index 4 has frag_index 3) will work with these fixes.  It does so because the failure handling on revert will push one of the nodes indexes to a handoff node when it fails to sync with it's target primary location because of 409, making room to receive the revert from the other primary while the handoff location will eventually push back to the other primary.

3 goes to handoff, 4 goes 3, handoff goes to 3

This shuffle might actually be *better* in some ways than letting multiple fragment indexes pile up on a single disk.

Also swaps are all but impossible given a reasonable amount of devices to support the ec scheme (maybe 2-3x) and the rebalance handling of partition movement.

The most likely failures are double handoff (where timestamp overlaps would allow the first handoff to be holding *all* the handoff fragment indexes until the primaries come back online given the current revert behavior) or a handoff becoming a primary (where timestamp overlaps might actually help because you can rebuild a missing fragment even before the previously a handoff, now primary, can revert it's current fragment).

Lot to think about, I'm probably not describing it well and definitely missing some stuff - maybe some of this needs to be discussed in Vancouver?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-18 00:47:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

(5 comments)

There's good fixes in here, only +1 because of my query about the probe test tearDown cleaning up killed drives.

But...fixing the node['index'] key error means we're now attempting reverts to handoffs rather than quietly failing to try, and where there is *any* fragment in conflict we can now end up with other fragments duplicated on two handoffs (or possibly more if there is a chain reaction) - see my mod to the probe test here [1]. 

So as it stands the 409 prevents one handoff accumulating lots of frag indexes, but we can end up with (lots of objects) having same frag index on multiple handoffs.

Working through this left me with the question - how do we end up with a fragment index on the wrong primary*? Because that's the only scenario where I can make sense of reverting *to* a handoff - why would we ever want to revert from a handoff to another handoff? Which is what the new probe test perfectly illustrates.

(* Is it after a rebalance?)

So should the revert job only call get_more_nodes if the local node is a primary?

Phew! roll on Vancouver!

[1] https://gist.github.com/alistairncoles/d3a01afe146c98e3f338

[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/174875/"}, {'account_id': 15090, 'date': '2015-04-20 12:38:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-04-20 17:59:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(5 comments)

Ah ha!  Yes the 409 being basically an unhandled failure of ssync causing duplication of data without proper cleanup is exactly the kind of thing I was worried about - thanks acoles!

So on the revert case we have options:

1) Do nothing.  Any attempt to revert anywhere besides the primary target for the fragment index fails loud and early.  Not terrible.
2) Fix the 409.  Allow ssync to place multiple fragment index on the same node simultaneously - not without risk - but the most obvious place we'd expect this to happen (revert to "better" handoff) is still broken.
3) Fix revert to handoff to not KeyError.  Introducing a risk that a 409 would leave a half synced suffix with duplicated data on the target and no cleanup.

... so for now maybe #1 is the best?!

Going all the way back to the beginning - it was not difficult in the early days to draw up scenarios where a node would be holding a fragment index that didn't match it's node index (most often citied case is a handoff node holding a fragment becoming a primary for the partition after a rebalance, most likely *not* assigned the node index for the handoff fragment he happened to be holding.).  It was much harder to know back then how the reconstructor and ssync where *actually* going to work.  At this point I'm *really* glad the data model can support multiple fragment archives on the same node - but not sure how often we should choose to wield this power (or how much we should actively try to avoid it!).

I should probably split the primary node fix out to a separate change - it's mostly a no brainer, not a high priority for rc2 but also not really related to the revert mess.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-04-20 20:47:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-20 22:38:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

There's also option 3b) make ssync a little less touchy about errors - for example, right now any 409 during ssync updates will cause it to to return False, {} - but it completed missing_checks and knows of any in-sync can-delete-objects on the rx !?! Consequently not only might we get duplicated frags on two handoffs when there is a single conflict during reverts, but if a new object PUT then causes another conflict on the next reconstructor run then the duplicates will still not be deleted (because ssync has this all or none 'failure' behavior), and so on.

Whereas... if ssync, on catching an updates failure, returned False, {objects known to be in sync from missing checks} then we would at least clean up duplicates on second reconstructor pass. That seems like low hanging fruit.

Better still, should we make ssync report individual update success by having the rx return hashes of successful updates?? So then we eliminate duplicates cos the sender's can-delete-objs would include all successfully updated objs. But thats a protocol change..."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-04-21 10:43:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-18 00:06:13.000000000', 'message': "Use the right nodes and frag_index on failures

On a revert:

If the primary node for a fragment index is unavailable, the next best place
for it is on one of the current handoff nodes in the ring (so the proxy can
find it!).  However, when we ssync to handoff node we need to make sure the
Frag-Index header is correct for the fragments we want to send in the job.

While generally the node's index is correct (espeically for sync jobs where
the job's frag_index is acctually different from the partners node index which
we acctually want to sync with) - on a handoff node there is no node index, so
we need to fill it in with the frag_index.  This fixes a KeyError when trying
to ssync to a handoff node.

On a sync:

If the primary left or right hand partners are down, the next best thing is to
validate the rest of the primary nodes.  Where the rest should exclude not
just the left and right hand partners - but ourself as well.

This fixes a accidental noop when partner node is unavailable and another node
is missing data.

Validation:

Add two more probetests to cover ssync failures for the primary sync_to nodes
on both revert and sync jobs.

Drive-by:

Make additional plumbing for the check_mount and check_dir constraints into
the remaining daemons.

Change-Id: I4d1c047106c242bca85c94b569d98fd59bb255f4

commit_message:
Exclude local_dev from sync partners on failure

If the primary left or right hand partners are down, the next best thing
is to validate the rest of the primary nodes.  Where the rest should
exclude not just the left and right hand partners - but ourself as well.

This fixes a accidental noop when partner node is unavailable and
another node is missing data.

Validation:

Add probetests to cover ssync failures for the primary sync_to nodes for
sync jobs.

Drive-by:

Make additional plumbing for the check_mount and check_dir constraints into
the remaining daemons.

Change-Id: I4d1c047106c242bca85c94b569d98fd59bb255f4

@Ihar: I disagree. There has been a conversation about this on the openstack-dev thread as well, but the gist of it is that from a stack-analytics perspective, if you back ported a fix, this gives you credit for the work involved in doing so. 

Even if it's just a clean cherry pick, the person doing the cherry pick has to identify the fix, cherry pick the fix and go through the git review process. Without the co-authored-by tag in the commit message that work is lost and uncredited from a Stack-Analytics perspective.

If you further disagree, then we probably need to get someone to clarify how this should be done, because that's the conclusion I came to based on the -dev mailing list discussions."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-03-02 10:36:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Pass '--dhcp-authoritative' option to dnsmasq

When dnsmasq is restarted, it forgets about all leases (since it runs
with leasefile-ro option). When client tries to renew its lease, dnsmasq
sends DHCPNAK reply with message "lease not found". Then client shuts
down the network and re-request lease from DHCP server (and gets exactly
same IP address). There's a small network downtime which affects
services, like zookeeper, running in VMs.

Change-Id: Ieff0236670c1403b5d79ad8e50d7574c1b694e34
Closes-Bug: #1345947
(cherry picked from commit 74a16fde1c9972dc3c5d07215ca9d5e8f2e23d70)

Rename sla.base module to sla

Since rally/benchmark/sla dir contains only one module, we can easaly remove
it and move rally.benchmark.sla.base to rally.benchmark.sla

Change-Id: If0f0a091af3b3451b81123434cafea57318b589f

     some/module.py -> some.py

So we should remove all *.pyc files before launching `testr --coverage`

Change-Id: Ica22a3cd1a26d27c01f314a48a7cd49a529552eb

commit_message:
Improvement of cover script

*.pyc files break cover-script for situations like:
     some/module.py -> some.py

So we should remove all *.pyc files before launching `testr --coverage`

Change-Id: Ica22a3cd1a26d27c01f314a48a7cd49a529552eb

commit_message:
Add mellanox package to target centos image

Add mlnx-ofed-light to the list of packages installed during target
centos image building.

Change-Id: I32a71181b16bb3897b9743efdb083057daf7bb96
Related-Bug: #1405661

commit_message:
Register oslo.log's config options in tests

When running tests with testr oslo.log's config options are always
registered even if you're only running one test. When you wish to debug
into your tests and use python -m testtools.run these options will not
be registered.

Closes-bug: 1433785
Change-Id: Ie3426cee8cd3f6f1222529160d39b281af5ce317

Thank you for putting this together.  A lot of work.  I have made some comments in-line.  My main concern is with the inconsistency in handling cases where we have:

msg = _LE("something %(somevar)s")
LOG.error(msg, {'somevar', var})

There are a number of cases where you collapse this down but a number where you don't.  I know that doing this is fine if the msg is used for LOG.error and then in an exception.  If, however, msg is just being used in one place I think we should make it all one LOG.error(_LE(...)) .

I noted a number of the places where it was happening.  Tried to get at least once per file that was doing that.  I didn't note very single instance though.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-04-13 20:09:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Fix missing translations for log messages

Fixed log translations in volume.drivers and volume.manager modules
for error, info and warning messages with appropriate marker function
according to the logging standards [1].

As LOG.warn has deprecated [2] so I have changed LOG.warn to
LOG.warning.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html
[2] http://bugs.python.org/issue13235

Note: Any new occurrences added in master during the review can be
handled separately if they are not caught by hacking checks.

Partial-Bug: 1431256
Change-Id: I9b7b89097b296ea62b43f1d948dcf59e2e5a40c4

commit_message:
Wait some time before checking puppet state

This tries to fix really strange bug. Puppet finished
its run without any error but for some reason last_run_summary.yaml
was not updated immediately.
If puppet finishes and last_run_summary.yaml is not updated we assume
that puppet crushed.

Change-Id: I81cc57564089dfbe937dd7e447b65fe645c8bae9
Closes-bug: #1458780

commit_message:
Add forgotten mellanox support for image-based-provisioning

The patchset adds section to boothook which configures kernel module
options and loads it. Also adds support to fuel-agent to deal with it.

Closes-Bug: #1405661
Change-Id: I1ec2caa674466c54534025d867be91fc19d078e4

subject: Uncomment [filter: keystoneauth] and [filter: authtoken] sessions
messages:
[{'account_id': 16233, 'date': '2015-05-26 22:00:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2015-05-26 22:31:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'm sorry, but IMHO this makes no sense, for 2 reasons

#1 These sections are not in the supplied pipeline, and if you add new items to the pipeline, you may as well uncomment the samples.

#2 One of these is not even a part of Swift.

I may be wrong, but there's no way for the reported bug 1459022 to be caused by the use of an unmodified sample file."}, {'account_id': 2696, 'date': '2015-05-26 22:35:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Those don't appear in the pipeline do they?  How do they break something when uncommented in the *sample* file?

The bug report looks a bit light on why a -sample file breaks an actual proxy-server trying to start up..."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-26 22:44:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- check-swift-dsvm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/55/185755/1/check/check-swift-dsvm-functional/87d0a41/ : SUCCESS in 22m 01s'}, {'account_id': 16233, 'date': '2015-05-26 23:31:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So Pet:
# 1 - These sections are on file and different from others they are commented.

# 2 - The error (LookupError: In section 'authtoken' (prefixed by 'filter') found in config /etc/swift/proxy-server.conf), this is the bug description. This error happens because as the 'authtoken' session is commented it is "invisible" and your items are not used. Likewise does the 'keystoneauth'.

Darrell:

The error does not happen because the sessions are uncommented but because they are commented and items can not be used'}, {'account_id': 16233, 'date': '2015-05-27 01:43:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-27 02:20:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

- gate-swift-tox-func http://logs.openstack.org/55/185755/2/check/gate-swift-tox-func/c55d463/ : SUCCESS in 4m 58s (non-voting)
- check-tempest-dsvm-full http://logs.openstack.org/55/185755/2/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full/0ba064a/ : SUCCESS in 36m 31s
- check-grenade-dsvm http://logs.openstack.org/55/185755/2/check/check-grenade-dsvm/00ccd31/ : SUCCESS in 37m 01s
- check-swift-dsvm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/55/185755/2/check/check-swift-dsvm-functional/af69fcc/ : SUCCESS in 15m 10s'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2015-05-27 02:22:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

This is a little better, but they are still not part of the pipeline (and are not mandatory pipeline modules).'}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-05-27 02:35:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Mauricio, I'm sorry this patch is not useful as default configuration. 

Current pipeline in the proxy-server.conf-sample is the following.

===
pipeline = catch_errors gatekeeper healthcheck proxy-logging cache container_sync bulk tempurl ratelimit tempauth container-quotas account-quotas slo dlo proxy-logging proxy-server
===

If there is a middleware which is in the pipeline, it should be described in each section like [fileter:authtoken].

In the bug #1459022, I think the deployer added the entry for authtoken in the pipleline for his environment but there was no change for the related section. When deployers use keystone as an authorization system, this patch is useful but it can not be default configuration and it's depends on deployers."}, {'account_id': 2696, 'date': '2015-05-27 05:05:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I still don't think this patch adds anything; if you add keystone stuff to the pipeline, you must make sure there are correctly-configured, uncommented sections for them."}, {'account_id': 12332, 'date': '2015-05-27 11:42:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Mauricio - By any chance you copied the sample proxy-server.conf file and updated the pipeline to have keystone middleware? If you did, you need to uncomment the appropriate sections for the middleware that you added and configure them accordingly. As Bishop, said I don't the patch is needed here for the sample."}, {'account_id': 16233, 'date': '2015-05-27 12:07:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hisashi, Thanks for the comments, every time I did the swift deployment was necessary to add these settings. So I thought it would be necessary to have it in the sample file, but after their consideraçõs I realized that maybe this is not necessary. Thank you'}, {'account_id': 16233, 'date': '2015-05-27 12:10:19.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/76/185176/2/check/noop/c96cbed/ : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 406, 'date': '2015-05-26 22:26:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

Folks, I've seen a failed Chris C.'s deployment on ~20 hardware nodes. When many nodes simultaneously load narrow Internet channel, it can become really slow. apt-get would fail way earlier anyway if connection is lost. It is running while connection is present, so why would we have such small timeout?

I'm for 1800s, even if it seems too large. If many nodes are fetching data from 40kbps channel - it starts to make a total sense to me.

For long term solution we'd definitely need to think about apt proxy. Ryan, please create a bug to consider apt-proxy."}, {'account_id': 8829, 'date': '2015-05-27 04:21:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-27 04:22:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Increase timeout for apt-get update task

On slow connections 3 minutes is not always sufficient
for the update to complete.

Change-Id: I8b7ca2fd5ef35bfc67d73c5ead6f85a01bfcf05e
Closes-bug: #1459089

commit_message:
Add warning about customized ubuntu mirrors

If a user adds custom ubuntu upstream mirrors to their environment, the
--clear-upstream-repos option does not automatically remove them from
the environment. This commit adds a warning to indicate that user
intervention may be required.

Change-Id: Iafc745cc53768f5de1765a07e8c5d333f4849c51
Partial-Bug: 1458597

commit_message:
Fix command line arguments has lower priority than config file

  *This bug happened because of how oslo is handling the order of command line

  *Make sure the command line parameter will always send last

Change-Id: Ia106ce2bd2994c494a6c25039d92358eeb0abdb9
Closes-Bug: #1454111

commit_message:
Move qemu-utils into install/defaults/main

Qemu-utils package is required for the qemu-img command, which is
required by diskimage-builder and therefor should be installed for all
environments, not just testing environments.

Change-Id: Id24c481455a0ab3cf5bf0ab96c233db2aadec62b

The changes as done in vertica/api.py would also need to go in mongodb/api.py'}, {'account_id': 6160, 'date': '2015-05-11 16:32:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(1 comment)

Mongodb is little different. it provisions config server and query router for which one cannot specify any parameters like nics/flavors/az, as these two instance types are not explicitly mentioned in the cluster create call. I can still use the network/az information provided on the instance to provision rest of the cluster instances but then these special instance types will be provisioned without any network, which will make it inconsistent.

I am  working on blueprint/spec, to address provisioning larger cluster where in most of these parameters (like flavor, volume, nics etc) will be supplied on the cluster level, which will also be used to address specific instances types which are provisioned behind the scenes. 

So if everybody is ok, I would like to get this change merged in for vertica for now and address mongodb as part of the change for the other blueprint.'}, {'account_id': 6160, 'date': '2015-05-11 16:35:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 1870, 'date': '2015-05-11 17:30:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 14991, 'date': '2015-05-11 17:33:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-11 18:48:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified+1

commit_message:
accepting network and availability zone for instances in cluster

Standalone instance create call in trove already accepts neutron networks
and availability zone information.

In the similar manner, instances which are part of the cluster can
now be supplied with a specific neutron network information and
availability zone.

This review is addressing the fix only for vertica datastore.

Partial-Bug: #1447350
Change-Id: I5a1e9300dd0a16395769acda672943899f9ad0ad

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-05-26 12:35:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hi Nikola, I'm sorry you couldn't attend the summit. There were some talks and decisions in this regard.
The device names in BDM is one of the features required for EC2 API.
Unfortunately in your absence nobody else could've commented upon the fate of the device names which started to disintegrate before our eyes ever since bdm v2 was introduced (please forgive me if I'm not exactly precise in some facts).
The thing is, right now nova's EC2 API being officially deprecated and all of the accent put into making external EC2 API (the one on stackforge) ready for production, it is required for some really important features to have device names, because they are the key for various operations performed by EC2 API. As it is, before the bdm v2 there was almost all we needed in terms of this functionality in public APIs present. Since then we're struggling.
What was discussed during the summit is that we'll need to bring back necessary features, providing required specs and reviews:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/YVR-nova-contributor-meetup
I suggest to understand what are the causes actually making you to go on removing all this stuff. Am I correct that it's caused by you thinking that there is no demand for it in the public APIs and that since it was not universally supported by some backends it should be removed everywhere?
If that's the case, I believe we should go the other way around and restore all of this, adding maybe tickets or limitations for some backends not supporting it.
Our features we have problems with now are device names everywhere, modification of deleteOnTermination flag, ability to change parameters upon volume attach and  deleteOnTermination and size attributes not stored anymore in snapshots.
Sorry if this review is not the very best place for this discussion we can move it anywhere else, but it just came up right after the summit talks, so it might be a good place to start."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-05-26 16:06:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hey Alexandre:

Yes - this is not the right place to have this discussion - I propose we take it to the ML - I will respond in short tho.

1) This patch only removes it from the CLI - it is still available in the API - so you can remove the -1. If someone is using this client he is most certainly using the OpenStack API so any issues related to the EC2 API are orthogonal to this patch

2) Most of the concerns you mention in your comment seem to be either bugs that are probably easy to fix (delete on termination for example), or just stem from not understanding what BDM v2 does (it removes nothing, it's still possible to use old syntax and never worry about it)

3) Device names are problematic because they DO NOT WORK for KVM guests. Exposing them in the API may make your API look like it's doing what you want but it doesn't. People using the EC2 API for Nova clouds need to be aware of this.

Let's take it to the ML for some further discussion - but it seems to me that whatever is missing for the EC2 API to work is fixing bugs that snuck in when the new extended format was added."}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2015-05-26 17:55:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2015-05-26 18:23:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-05-26 20:28:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I can remove -1 if you think I should. But I'm still personally against such changes and drops of existing functionality partially because some people might use it and as you mentioned some bugs can sneak in. Overall I'm against this until it's collectively decided in nova what should be done with this functionality in all of the affected areas - for example, if it should somehow (maybe with inconsistencies and limitations) work for EC2 API, then maybe it should provide the same functionality in native API as well. From what I understood during the summit this matter is rather vague for everyone so can we first clarify it and then move on with reviews?"}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-05-27 10:44:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

Alexander - Fair enough. If we aim to provide good support the EC2 API we need to carefully rethink where we go with this. Let me start a thread about this on the ML and we can coordinate there.'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-05-27 10:44:21.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

As per the discussion inline'}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-05-27 11:08:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you Nikola. I've started the thread earlier."}]

commit_message:
Remove device arg from nova volume-attach

For libvirt only clouds - passing this is almost always a mistake, for
other hypervisors, it's not mandatory anyway (Nova will choose an
available one because it's needed by the database) - but this kind of
low level detail is really not something that makes sense exposed through
the public API.

We can't phase it out as easily from the API, but we can easily
disallow it in the CLI as a first step towards removing it's usage.

Change-Id: I6dd534c659d0b548375405b5589fbad0197125bf

commit_message:
hadoop-cdh: simplify package installation

Move the repository addition in a pre-install.d script, as that is the
right place for such operations (no more need to manual `apt-get update`
run), and switch it from curl to wget (already in use in that script);
as a result, wget is now installed in pre-install.d.

The above change makes the installation of hadoop-hdfs-namenode and
hadoop-hdfs-datanode possible using the declarative package-installs
way.

As a side effect of installing packages before setting up the hadoop
user and group, make sure to not create them if already present. The
packaging as of today takes care of creating the hadoop group, so guard
the setup in case it is not done anymore or will be done for the user
too.

Change-Id: I248872e77358f8388f4a66a54e53b2ffa727c7e3

commit_message:
Fix Neutron L3 destructive tests by using proper SSH connection

After a controller rebooted/destroyed, check_instance_connectivity
should use remote connetion to an online controller that wont be
rebooted. Will be used controller from which L3 router agent
is removed.

Change-Id: I19328dfd4bb8ffbf2035197395fa6c3067a01384
Closes-Bug:#1458020

commit_message:
Use the status defined in bay object Status class

Currently, we defined a status class in bay object file, it will be indicate
the bay's status(actually, it reuses heat's stack status), but we don't use
Status anywhere, this patch uses there status defined in Status.

Closes-Bug: #1459104
Change-Id: I5ed40bfb93f5246777643912de3e98bc3400bcab

commit_message:
Removed memcached log directory task

The memcached play has a log directory task that will cause an issue
with permissions with a container where memcached is installed. To
solve this issue the log directory permissions change task needs to
be removed

Change-Id: I7daa76e601a1bf430765866c1e4c0b8f9638aa73
Closes-Bug: 1459039
(cherry picked from commit ca9cbb8f8ff2f3bfb96f96ae3c2cbd5300fe3348)

commit_message:
Using muranoclient for obtain package list

Fixes incorrect logic of get_list_packages function in tests.
Now for obtaining package list in tests will be used muranoclient
instead of requests library.

Change-Id: I215937cd058adb66ac6e573601490791dad5eb4a
Closes-Bug: #1458646

commit_message:
Document the testing effort on OpenFlow stateful firewalling

This patch introduces the testing directory and a proposed
architecture for testing OpenFlow stateful firewalling vs
the current iptables based firewall which combines
OVS+LB+iptables+ipsets.

Change-Id: I5204782eeef4b84285142ad4b67e9a9376193455

commit_message:
autohelp: generate rst tables

We are mmoving the guides to RST, so we need config-reference tables in
this format. This patch adds a `rst` subcommand to autohelp.py to handle
this new requirement.

RST has limited tables-related features, and openstackdocstheme will
need an update to improve the output.

Change-Id: I5e58d60e2308d208e850f903559da5f5a6a949e3

commit_message:
run-upgrade.sh: add a missing redirect

When adding rabbit_cluster_name: rpc to the user variables, it just
echoed it and did not redirect the output to add it to the
user_variables.yml file.

Change-Id: Idddc9eedf868f1312d7a449bba7079d207309538
(cherry picked from commit a2a4bb6e3bab097017aa544d109a4e5f69b48dc2)

commit_message:
Reuse the various service passwords as db passwords.

We need to stop using "unset" as the password for all databases. Ideally we
would add a "XxxxDSN" parameter (e.g. KeystoneDSN) but this wont work because
we don't know the VirtualIP to pass in.

Until we can come up with a better solution we should at least get rid of
the "unset" passwords.

Change-Id: I31f45912fa9c116ccdee010a2c5d91ea43a25671
Depends-On: I8ffe1eb481f615b0fbe127cd8107f1e70794c839

commit_message:
Add handler flushing to roles that need it

This patch adds handler flushing as the last task in each role to ensure
that there are log files present when the rsyslog client configuration
task is executed a little later in the playbook that consumes the role.

Closes-Bug: #1458822
Change-Id: I92a26b620aa7bc0fbe33175594d37da7d5aca7df

commit_message:
Add the rebinding chance in _bind_port_if_needed

Make function _bind_port_if_needed to bind at least one time when the port's
binding status passed in is already in binding_failed.

Co-Autored-By: Eugene Nikanorov <enikanorov@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I823ff5ca66833cdca459f13ab28f5075ae03ded5
Closes-Bug: #1399249

commit_message:
Updated Kilo to use the head of the kilo branches

This commit revs all services, and other to use the head of the
stable/kilo branches. This change brings in various bug fixes
and updates that will allow us to ensure that we have a stable and
capable deployment system.

Change-Id: I9badd032554000d0f4ea42f0d17c43ececd8ad9a
Closes-Bug: 1451860

Closes-Bug: 1459039

commit_message:
Removed memcached log directory task

The memcached play has a log directory task that will cause an issue
with permissions with a container where memcached is installed. To
solve this issue the log directory permissions change task needs to
be removed

Change-Id: I7daa76e601a1bf430765866c1e4c0b8f9638aa73
Closes-Bug: 1459039

commit_message:
Stop registering opt fatal_exception_format_errors in cinder.exp

Given cinder switched to use oslo.versionedobject, and the opt has
been registered by versionedobject.expection, we need to stop
registering opt fatal_exception_format_errors in cinder.expection,
or it will cause errors and cinder-api cannot be started.

Closes-Bug: #1458448

Change-Id: Ia1a99a08c3e74fe737b3f091751689654cd49e2f

commit_message:
Add setup/cleanup_instance_network_on_host api for neutron/nova-network

When reschedule/unshelve/evacuate/rebuild instance, the instance
is moved from one host to another. The network should be updated
for the instance. And there are similar APIs
migrate_instance_start/stop, those two APIs should be used for
migration case as the name. So adds new APIs used to update
network resource when instance is moved.

This patch implements the new APIs both for neutron and
nova-network.

(cherry picked from commit 7368d9f6e9e94819b199d0f2cc1ac69706870586)

Change-Id: I513e0a08b32aa7f38c480488b398cd97d8cdc471
Related-bug: #1327124

commit_message:
Update network resource when rescheduling instance

When instance building failed, compute manager will try to reschedule
the failed instance. If the network resource already allocated before
failed, the network resource need update at current compute node and
next compute node.

Before rescheduling the failed instance, for nova-network with multihost,
because the network already setup on the compute node, the floating ip
should be cleanup at compute node.

After rescheduling, because the network already allocated, then compute
manager won't allocate network again. For neutron, the port binding info
need update to new compute node. For nova-network with multihost, the
floating ip should be setup on the new compute node.

(cherry picked from commit 05cd4824a9749c6067bb3eddc0994126d8940941)

Change-Id: Id4822ca0a902b35396025bde2a16411a02c46e0e
Closes-Bug: #1327124

commit_message:
Map Cinder services to isolated networks

This change adds parameters to specify which networks the Cinder API and
Cinder iSCSI services will listen on. If the internal_api network exists,
Cinder API will be bound to the IP on that network, otherwise it will
default to the Undercloud 'ctlplane' network. The Cinder iSCSI service will
bind to the storage network if it exists, otherwise will also default to
using the Undercloud 'ctlplane' network.

Change-Id: I98149f108baf28d46eb199b69a72d0f6914486fd

commit_message:
Map Ceilometer services to isolated networks

This change adds the parameters to specify which networks the Ceilometer
and MongoDB servers listen on. It is set to the internal_api network if
present, and reverts to the default Undercloud 'ctlplane' network if not.

Change-Id: Ib646e4a34496966f9b1d454f04d07bf95543517f

commit_message:
Update hacking version to fix pep8 gate job

Any new failing rules have just been added to ignore for now, so
that the gate can be unblocked quickly, although future changes
which un-ignore those rules would be welcome.

Change-Id: I5861ab178ae8bf4861c93941c33b551b7f90e835

commit_message:
Add NM_CONTROLLED=no to each interface configuration

In order to allow os-net-config to coexist with NetworkManager, this
patch adds NM_CONTROLLED=no to the top of each interface configuration.
This ensures that NetworkManager will not mess with interfaces that are
configured by os-net-config.

Change-Id: I9d226e032eb1cb411b6ea617936f4425c7fd2c74

commit_message:
Add sshutils._put_file_shell

Some images such as cirros have no SFTP client installed.
Implemented function `sshutils._put_file_shell' generates
a simple shell script that uploads the file as a here-doc.

Change-Id: I93626ee6ff8dc75cb94adaabf7c4f419367b58d1
Implements: blueprint vm-workloads-framework

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

commit_message:
Fix bug in OSTF Heat tests

In case of previous implementation of _create_stack():

    stack_name = rand_name('ost1_test-')
    client.stacks.create(stack_name=stack_name,
                         template=template,
                         parameters=parameters,
                         disable_rollback=disable_rollback)
    stack = self._find_stack(client, 'stack_name', stack_name)
    self.addCleanup(self._delete_stack, stack.id)

the following situation was possible: if _find_stack doesn't get
list of stacks in 20 sec (timeout), step will fail with timeout error
and addCleanup() won't get 'stack.id',that's why created stack won't be
deleted.

Change-Id: I72330d18e95207e9e7fa454a78bcf1cab7dbd2f0
Closes-Bug: #1458639

commit_message:
Fix overwrite of params in SF image cache update

In the update cache volume routine of the SolidFire driver
we're unintentionally re-initializing the params variable
when assigning volID as opposed to just appending another key
to it.

This patch fixes that.

Change-Id: I213776ee6aef6e5dee2807c19b7eea05af23d6c0
Closes-Bug: #1454425

commit_message:
Make create commands cut long output

 * When we use workflow-create of action-create cmds,
   client uses default format function for output the data.
   But in case long strings (e.g. a lot of input keys to
   workflow or action) table is crashed by these long strings.
   Using format_list function solves the problem.

Change-Id: Id4b7594c6873e29b45d2b53417d316e0ed5b1e39

commit_message:
VLAN support fix.

The solution is compatible with the existing VLAN flows:
 - inbound in br-int that converts the global vlan to the local
 - outbound in br-{eth} that convert the local vlan to the global one

The initialization is done in the set_controller method after that the controller is sets:
 - the physical bridges rules are reinitiliazed, without the drop flow. packet with the global vlan must also be forwarded.
      - low priority normal flow
      - flows that changes the local vlan id to the global one
 - For br-int:
      - in the table #60 the VLAN global VID from the TUN_ID for inter-network traffic is set
      - the flows that change the global vlan id to the local one

Change-Id: Ifdc78c6edbe2dc3cef4107fbfb44613b6ae025d1

commit_message:
Sync ports on L2 Agent startup

This patch sync all the ports with the L3 application on the
L3 Agent startup.
This fixes a bug that was noticed during L3 agent startup,
as the local structures are empty (for ports data).

Before the agent is started it reads all the ports/subnets/networks
information, build port dictionaries and send that data to the
application.
A special flag was added to the sync_port method in order to
recognize that this is not a live port update and no flows
updates should be sent

Change-Id: If82be23264b5122e86aad5124e2dbc5649deb868

commit_message:
Make v3 auth work for Swift

Plumb through the paste-deploy config options into the auth-middleware
section of the global CONF object. This should let Swift operators and
other consumers of the paste-deploy API use v3 auth.

Change-Id: Icc1c4ba5bf7ef113a7a36029834d722e3f39cf7a

- gate-training-guides-tox-slides http://logs.openstack.org/31/170731/1/check/gate-training-guides-tox-slides/9d0b4ee/ : SUCCESS in 1m 38s'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-04-07 12:39:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the patch Roger. We need to also add some warnings to this feature which should preferably be blocking the script for confirmation and ask the user if they understand that the cluster may break (I am afraid of the database entries on the controller node). Another possible workaround for this is to delete the db tables and repopulate them (${
openstack-service}-manage db_sync)'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2015-04-11 05:29:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sure, we can add warnings, but anyone who uses the dev tools in the tools folder should realize that they may have to spend 10 minutes rebuilding their cluster from scratch if things go wrong.

However, if the patch works as expected (and so far nobody has shown that it doesn't), we don't have to worry about the database entries on the controller node, because _all_ nodes are restored to the exact on-disk state they had at the chosen point during a regular rebuild.

The only significant difference when rebuilding from snapshots is that the nodes are not given plenty of time to boot up and start their services before the cluster build continues. So if scripts start using services that are usually already up (because at this point during a regular build, the controller node has been running for a couple of minutes or more), they may be in for an unpleasant surprise, and the build will fail. That way, unsafe assumptions are uncovered and can be fixed."}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-04-13 08:05:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the explaination Roger. I think you are right. I did not realize that changing a snapshot on network/compute node would also revert back the snapshots on the controller node. As of waiting for VMs to come up, it would be great to add wait for the VM to boot (via. ssh) as it is done for other nodes.'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2015-04-13 18:14:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I didn't try, but we should be able to just call wait_for_ssh.

But it wouldn't be much better than just sleeping for 10 seconds. The ssh server is not the dependency, and if the actual dependencies come up after ssh, it's just a coincidence.

Sure, we could say "who cares if it works?". The problem with this approach is that it has a fair chance of turning a race that results in failure every time or often into a race that happens so rarely it becomes difficult to fix.

I think the best approach is to test building from each snapshot a dozen times or so and fix any bad assumptions in the client-side scripts about services being up when they are not (yet). It is simple, we already wait for services to come up in many places.'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-05-08 09:09:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ok, I am fine with this approach. If Sayali agrees, we could get this merged and test it eventually. [{'created': '2015-04-05 19:06:23.000000000', 'message': 'labs: repeat test from snapshot

With this changeset, the cluster build can be tested starting from a
specific snapshot. This is mostly useful for testing client scripts
without having to go through the whole cluster build every time.

For instance, to rebuild the cluster from snapshot neuntron_configured:

./tools/repeat-test.sh -b -t neutron_configured -s "controller compute"

This will restore the appropriate snapshot on each node, boot nodes

commit_message:
labs: repeat test from snapshot

With this changeset, the cluster build can be tested starting from a
specific snapshot. This is mostly useful for testing client scripts
without having to go through the whole cluster build every time.

For instance, to rebuild the cluster from snapshot neuntron_configured:

./tools/repeat-test.sh -b -t neutron_configured -s "controller compute"

This will restore the appropriate snapshot on each node, boot nodes
controller and compute, and continue the cluster build from the named
snapshot onward.

Note: this procedure restores, boots, and continues in short order which
uncovers new shortcomings (races) in scripts that assume a service is
available when they should check and wait for the service.

If you just want to restore all nodes to the appropriate snapshots:
./tools/restore-cluster.sh -t <snapshot>

Change-Id: I0b7888d02de6eb50760d421d6d897f516f8c7718

commit_message:
Change the order of PTL, APC, and ATC slides

This change reverses the order of the PTL, APC, and ATC slides in
response to student feedback in the last two Upstream training sessions.

Change-Id: I95ec52898115ecec37f084efb476db82e4f38658
Closes-Bug: #1457174

commit_message:
Remove TaskRunner from Volume resources

All the volume_tasks logic has been redistributed as methods of either
cinder or nova client plugins.

The logic of detaching was simplified and a check for out-of-band
changes is no longer executed.

The old VolumeAttachTask is left in place as it is still used in
creating the AWS::EC2::Instance resource.

Change-Id: I13f8e03ff090dd5f5739e5af231c77d066eb9eac
Partial-Bug: #1393268

Winston, you raise important issues and I have updated the commit message to clarify that this is a bug-fix for an issue in the field where our NFS drivers fail to honor an NFS over-provisioning configuration option that pre-dates the more general support for max_oversubscription_ratio introduced in kilo.

Going forwards, we need to either deprecate the older, NFS-only overprovisioning configuration options or re-implement support for them using the scheduler's computation of "virtual" free space rather than relying on driver reports of "apparent" free space.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-07 10:48:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1
