commit_message:
Move all_tenants and edit_managed attributes to designate Client

Initializing designate client with a pre-existing keystone session
won't work as designate expects keystone session to have the
'all_tenants' and 'edit_managed' attributes:

Example code:

    keystone_session = ksc_session.Session(
      auth=keystone_auth,
      verify=True,
      cert=my_cert
    )

than later:

    self._designate_client = designate_client(
      session=keystone_session,
      region_name=region_name
    )

with that code, wrap_api_call() will raise an exception:

  AttributeError: 'Session' object has no attribute 'all_tenants'

Same goes for 'edit_managed'.

This patch moves both attributes from Keystone session to designate
Client.

Closes-Bug: 1457821
Change-Id: I13d6c9ed46406fefc8cfa5de46811e4be009f1af

commit_message:
rabbit: Fix message ttl not work

impl_rabbit set timeout into message's header with {'ttl': (timeout * 1000)},
this mean doesn't work in real, messages still stays in queue after the ttl.

As RabbitMQ document said (http://www.rabbitmq.com/ttl.html#per-message-ttl),
we should passing "expiration" into message's property rather than header to
make it work.

Change-Id: I5d6ae72e69f856c56fb83fb939ed35246716e04d
Closes-bug: #1444854

[{'created': '2015-05-07 05:50:01.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: update supported plugins

commit_message:
VMware: update supported plugins

Add all of the supported plugins to the VMware plugin.py file.

The supported plugins are:
 - NSX MH
 - NSXv
 - Simple DVS (this does not support security groups and any layer
               functionality). Useful for testing of Neutron with VC.

Change-Id: I9e5c779127ff44674cb60f3c19d4b5c8bdae6101

commit_message:
OVS-agent: Separate ovs-ofctl using code as a driver

This is a preparation to introduce another Ryu-based implementation.
The aim is to replace this with the new Ryu-based implementation
eventually.

Add a config option for OVS-agent which selects the implementation.
Currently, the only available choice is 'ovs-ofctl'.

Also, this commit simplifies DVR logics by reducing duplications
and makes some of DVR UTs actually check the flows rather than just
"add_flow is called".

Partially-Implements: blueprint ovs-ofctl-to-python
Change-Id: Ie1224f8a1c17268cd7d1c474ed82fdfb8852eaa8

commit_message:
Fix logging task id when task fails

We fail to correctly display the task id in couple of log messages.
This patch fixes it.

Closes-Bug: #1456388

Change-Id: I0da53a9fccf76480bcb3c81ff137543493d77991

commit_message:
Remove skip for bug 1439371 on test_volume_boot_pattern

The bug is reported as fixed on master (Liberty). Because of change
Iac44c6a84a39a518f4800483558bbe5223a41359 the ceph job doesn't run on
stable/icehouse or stable/juno, but we'd need to get the cinder fix
backported to proposed/kilo or stable/kilo before we could enable the
test again otherwise it will break stable kilo runs of the ceph job.

Cinder fix: I688898b3841691369d73887f7eabdceb05155db1

Related-Bug: #1439371

Change-Id: Iaeef2aaa3400cdd55a5ecbdfe7d492d7df560289

"}, {'created': '2015-04-28 17:55:17.000000000', 'message': "Fix redstack issues (plugin use, stop and start)

Due to having multiple patchsets in flight at the same time
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/158540/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/167047 and
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/155913 ),
'start' and 'stop' still relied on having the Trove setup support in
devstack (the lib/trove file).

This needs to be changed to use the devstack/plugin.sh file in the
Trove repo once the devstack code is gone.  If not, when the devstack
patchset merges (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/167447 ) the
'stop' and 'start' commands will stop working.

Also made the using the plugin dependent on having the devstack
setup code gone. This fixes the issue of having devstack start
up two sets of Trove services.

Change-Id: Ic1e5a809a47b3f00d5eaec30237e37b73c676aad
Closes-Bug: #1448189
"}, {'created': '2015-04-28 21:13:23.000000000', 'message': "Fix redstack issues (stop/start,plugin use,conf)

Due to having multiple patchsets in flight at the same time
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/158540/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/167047/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/155913/ and possibly others),
a number of things stopped working (mostly due to auto-merge issues).

1. 'start' and 'stop' still relied on having the Trove setup support in
devstack (the lib/trove file).
2. Two instances of the Trove services are started as devstack doesn't
check if a plugin is enabled when starting the same services.
3. The trove.conf.rc file in local.conf.d stopped being added to
local.conf, as the variable name 'TROVE_CONF' now conflicts with the
actual Trove service configuration file.
4. The localrc that was sourced previously is no longer available. The
generated file '.localrc.auto' needs to be sourced instead.

These issues were fixed as noted:

1. 'stop' and 'start' now depend on a variable to find the commands
file.  This variable is set to $PATH_DEVSTACK_SRC/lib/trove if it
exists, otherwise it's set to $DEST/devstack/plugin.sh  If neither
exists, redstack stops with an error.
2. If $PATH_DEVSTACK_SRC/lib/trove exists, redstack disables the
devstack Trove plugin under the assumption that devstack will set up
Trove based on its files.
3. The trove.conf.rc file was renamed to trove_services.conf.rc
4. '.localrc.auto' is sourced if it exists

Change-Id: Ic1e5a809a47b3f00d5eaec30237e37b73c676aad
Closes-Bug: #1448189
"}]
commit_message:
Fix redstack issues (stop/start,plugin use,conf)

Due to having multiple patchsets in flight at the same time
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/158540/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/167047/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/155913/ and possibly others),
a number of things stopped working (mostly due to auto-merge issues).

1. 'start' and 'stop' still relied on having the Trove setup support in
devstack (the lib/trove file).
2. Two instances of the Trove services are started as devstack doesn't
check if a plugin is enabled when starting the same services.
3. The trove.conf.rc file in local.conf.d stopped being added to
local.conf, as the variable name 'TROVE_CONF' now conflicts with the
actual Trove service configuration file.
4. The localrc that was sourced previously is no longer available. The
generated file '.localrc.auto' needs to be sourced instead.

These issues were fixed as noted:

1. 'stop' and 'start' now depend on a variable to find the commands
file.  This variable is set to $PATH_DEVSTACK_SRC/lib/trove if it
exists, otherwise it's set to $DEST/devstack/plugin.sh  If neither
exists, redstack stops with an error.
2. If $PATH_DEVSTACK_SRC/lib/trove exists, redstack disables the
devstack Trove plugin under the assumption that devstack will set up
Trove based on its files.
3. The trove.conf.rc file was renamed to trove_services.conf.rc
4. '.localrc.auto' is sourced if it exists

Change-Id: Ic1e5a809a47b3f00d5eaec30237e37b73c676aad
Closes-Bug: #1448189

commit_message:
Fix cli parser return empty list

Parsing cli output with no resources return empty list, otherwise
cli command return emty table with list of headers and empty values.

It is usefull somethimes check list attributes of resources.
Also the result of execution commands should be the same as in cli.

Change-Id: I1b3d771c59dffed4a2afcc760fd30e7b3b9e2bc0
Closes-Bug: #1458605

commit_message:
only force off KEYSTONE_USE_WSGI up until kilo

Keystone should be allowed to run in the wsgi mode in grenade, so stop
forcing this off for kilo and beyond upgrade testing.

Note: we also really should have an upgrade path from eventlet -> wsgi
tested, but that has not been done by the keystone team yet.

Change-Id: Ia4801bcd2278f39b17acb0883beec75b991b32df

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-25 13:04:27.000000000', 'message': 'Enable more tests on Python 3

* Trait.convert_value() now explicitly decodes byte strings from UTF-8:
  it fixes a BytesWarning error when Python 3 is run using -bb command
  line option
* Replace types.NoneType with type(None)
* fileutils.write_to_tempfile() expects content as bytes: encode the
  content on Python 3
* subprocess.Popen.communicate() returns stdout and stderr as bytes:
  check for pattern using byte strings
* Fix verify_signature() on Python 3: encode new signature to ASCII
* Replace "with contextlib.nested(...):" with two nested with,
  contextlib.nested() was removed in Python 3
* Fix import in test_messaging
* tox -e py34 now runs much more tests

Change-Id: If2a16c3b8ca64ca86d8172b36ecbf6298044ec87

commit_message:
Enable more tests on Python 3

* Trait.convert_value() now explicitly decodes byte strings from UTF-8:
  it fixes a BytesWarning error when Python 3 is run using -bb command
  line option
* Replace types.NoneType with type(None)
* fileutils.write_to_tempfile() expects content as bytes: encode the
  content on Python 3
* subprocess.Popen.communicate() returns stdout and stderr as bytes:
  check for pattern using byte strings
* Fix verify_signature() on Python 3: encode new signature to ASCII
* Replace "with contextlib.nested(...):" with two nested with,
  contextlib.nested() was removed in Python 3
* Fix import in test_messaging
* tox -e py34 now runs much more tests

Change-Id: If2a16c3b8ca64ca86d8172b36ecbf6298044ec87

commit_message:
Fix Metadef Object update issue with python-glanceclient

Disallowed fields(schema, created_at and updated_at) were
getting deleted from Metadef namespace instead of Metadef object.

Change-Id: Id80e204c7af1ac6926c66627d290a15c4e6b00d9
Closes-Bug: #1433884

[{'created': '2015-05-15 10:12:43.000000000', 'message': "Remove iscsi_helper calls from base iscsi driver

There are a number of drivers that inherit from the base
iscsi driver, using the base implementation of initialize_connection
and terminate_connection.  These drivers also don't have iscsi_helper
defined.

We've kept all iscsi_helper specific code in the tgt helpers
themselves, or in the various versions of the LVM driver
which is where they belong.

Over time however there have been some iscsi_helper specific
calls that have crept in to the base volume.driver:ISCSIDriver
class.  These were LIO specific calls and as a result when a
configuration is set with multi-backend to use lioadm as the
target helper, or even if it's not used but the default iscsi_helper
is set to lioadm the initialize_connection and terminate_connection
calls will try and access the LIO specific calls and raise because
the drivers inheriting from this class don't have target_helper
members.

This went unnoticed mostly because there's no significant LIO testing
in place and there were no distros setting LIO as the default iscsi_helper,
it appears that this has changed however.

This patch moves the LIO specific calls back where they belong
and keeps the base ISCSIDriver generic.  I've also added a test
case for this in the SolidFire driver because it's impacted by
this.

[Minor formatting changes from original patch to avoid E127 and H402]

Change-Id: Ibe010b62bb2518685753dd515326e56ffcc99cea
Closes-Bug: #1400804

"}]
commit_message:
Remove iscsi_helper calls from base iscsi driver

There are a number of drivers that inherit from the base
iscsi driver, using the base implementation of initialize_connection
and terminate_connection.  These drivers also don't have iscsi_helper
defined.

We've kept all iscsi_helper specific code in the tgt helpers
themselves, or in the various versions of the LVM driver
which is where they belong.

Over time however there have been some iscsi_helper specific
calls that have crept in to the base volume.driver:ISCSIDriver
class.  These were LIO specific calls and as a result when a
configuration is set with multi-backend to use lioadm as the
target helper, or even if it's not used but the default iscsi_helper
is set to lioadm the initialize_connection and terminate_connection
calls will try and access the LIO specific calls and raise because
the drivers inheriting from this class don't have target_helper
members.

This went unnoticed mostly because there's no significant LIO testing
in place and there were no distros setting LIO as the default iscsi_helper,
it appears that this has changed however.

This patch moves the LIO specific calls back where they belong
and keeps the base ISCSIDriver generic.  I've also added a test
case for this in the SolidFire driver because it's impacted by
this.

[Minor formatting changes from original patch to avoid E127 and H402]

Change-Id: Ibe010b62bb2518685753dd515326e56ffcc99cea
Closes-Bug: #1400804
(cherry picked from commit 7095e1c5a7477ca77c8698d96a969a7d78090a18)

commit_message:
Skip hbase tests on Python 3

The hbase driver requires the Python happybase module which is not
compatible with Python 3 yet.

* Fix run_with() of ceilometer.tests.db on Python 3: no need to get the
  __func__ attribute on Python 3, the method is bounded
* Skip hbase tests if the driver cannot be loaded
* Don't define the HBaseManager class if happybase cannot be imported
* Don't run tests with the hbase driver if the happybase cannot be
  imported

Change-Id: I07803446d089ed62c2368b4f76ff0e028fc4a3bd

commit_message:
Add filtering of Fixed network interface in case of bonds

Problem was that nailgun didn't check the presence of Fixed network on bond,
it'd only checked it on NICs. Simlar check for bond interfaces is added.

Change-Id: I7296b1724ac1af4c205854ebbd0ba0c292377032
Closes-Bug: #1457387

commit_message:
rabbit: remove publisher classes

Each times we send a message with the rabbit driver we create useless
object that's not more that the kombu exchange and a wrapper method around
the kombu producer.

So, this change just creates the exchange not our useless custom Publisher
and move the wrapped methods into the Connection object.

Change-Id: Id221f4363d897cd904f7aeccbc90cbd288db2db1

commit_message:
Always provide a tag when building with build-all-docker-images

When we're not providing a tag, the build script will use one based on
the short SHA of the tip of the current git branch.

Make the `build-all-docker-images` script always provide a tag to
`build-docker-image` in order to prevent issues with Docker not being
able to find the base image when changing branches during an ongoing
build.

Closes-Bug: #1458739
Change-Id: Id6925b792f46d14b20a7dbebfaf0d351ddec6538

commit_message:
Initial commit for functional tests

In this patchset added a starting point for running
ceilometer functional tests.
Next points include a creating scripts for using a different env setup
for different backends, creating a new job in openstack-infra/project-config
and separating ceilometer tests to unit and functional.

Partially implements: blueprint ceilometer-functional-tests

Change-Id: I3ecadd388812afde5c48aff8214597d76faccf33

> The way that this will work is python26 jobs will be removed from
> running on master and feature branches of projects that have
> stable/icehouse and/or stable/juno branches. The python26 jobs will
> still continue to run against the stable branches. Any project that is a
> library consumed by stable releases but does not have stable branches
> will have python26 run against that project's master branch. This is
> necessary to ensure we don't break backward compatibility with stable
> releases.
> 
> This essentially boils down to: no python26 jobs against server project
> master branches, but python26 jobs continue to run against stable
> branches. Python-*client and oslo projects[1] will continue to have
> python26 jobs run against their master branches. All other projects will
> have python26 jobs completely removed (including stackforge).

commit_message:
Make keystone optional

Add a new auth_strategy option allowing to disable keystone auth to make
CK fully standalone if needed/wanted.

Update the sample config file with the new option.

Change-Id: I8926f1518382640395e34b4e5321d99f2bc2d7eb

commit_message:
Add one more functional test for MessagingTimeout

Add a check, that MessagingTimeout raises on long-running queries,
if client sends another queries at the same time.

Added a long_running_task() to TestServerEndpoint and allowed to pass a
message executor into the RpcServerFixture.

Related bug: #1338732

Co-Authored-By: Roman Podoliaka <rpodolyaka@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: Icafb6838e2d9fb76b6d1c202465c09c174a3bed9

subject: rabbit: Set timeout on the underlying socket

commit_message:
rabbit: Set timeout on the underlying socket

They are some case where the underlying can be stuck
until the system socket timeout is reached, but in oslo.messaging
we very often known that is not needed to wait for ever because
the upper layer (usualy the application) expect to return after
a certain period.

So this change set the timeout on the underlying socket each we can
determine that is not needed to wait more.

Closes-bug: #1436788
Change-Id: Ie71ab8147c56eaf672585da107bec8b22af9da6c

commit_message:
Setup for translation

To start translation, we need to initially import the
translation file - and place it at the proper place so that
the usual CI scripts can handle it.

The proper place is for all python projects
$PROJECT/locale/$PROJECT.pot - see setup.cfg.

Note that we were using _i18n.py from openstack/common
which is likely to go away, so created our own i18n.py
module per best practices:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/usage.html#creating-an-integration-module

Further imports will be done by the OpenStack Proposal bot.

implements blueprint magnum-i18n-support
Change-Id: Ib34bfbe1ae47e077e92a4262642842c845d1a5d6

[{'created': '2015-05-13 19:58:41.000000000', 'message': "Minor install script improvements

* Install wget/curl with other software. Previously, wget was
  installed in its own special block, apart from
  install_required_sw(), where all other required software was
  installed. This may have been a slight micro-optimization since the
  script didn't have to check for wget or curl each time something was
  downloaded, any optimization was offset by an additional potential
  invocation of apt-get/yum and convoluted logic. wget is now
  installed in install_required_sw if neither wget nor curl is found.
* Remove two-argument die() in installation script. install_rally.sh
  provides two ways to stop execution: abort() and die(). The former
  takes one required argument (the exit code), and prints any
  additional arguments to stderr. The latter takes two required
  arguments (exit code and header) and then either prints additional
  arguments to stderr or, if there are none, prints anything passed to
  it on stdin to stderr. There are several places that use a
  two-argument die(), which happily waits for stdin forever. In other
  cases we had unique and exciting hacks to get around the strange
  usage pattern of die(), such as passing a newline to it or repeating
  the error message twice. This fixes all of those. It also removes
  the err() function, which was used in some other cases to print to
  stderr before stopping with good ol'-fashioned exit.
* Fix inconsistent say/echo in install_rally.sh install_rally.sh had a
  say() function that was basically echo with a prefix, but it was
  rarely used; echo was generally preferred. This eliminates say()
  entirely.
* Quoted things that need quoted. Some other minor changes
  recommended by shellcheck.

Change-Id: I1a9d0b2ff5daba02998245d5c7e624f46bd2242a

commit_message:
Minor install script improvements

* Install wget/curl in install_required_sw(), where all other required
  software is installed.
* Fix and standardize exit. install_rally.sh used three different ways
  to stop execution: abort(); die(); and err() + exit. die() has a
  strange usage pattern, and there are several places that use a
  two-argument die() which happily waits for stdin forever. In other
  cases we had unique and exciting hacks to get around die()'s
  strangeness. This fixes all of those, and makes everything either
  use abort() or die() (correctly).
* Fix inconsistent say()/echo usage. This eliminates the rarely-used
  say() function entirely.
* Quoted things that need quoted. Some other minor changes
  recommended by shellcheck.

Change-Id: I1a9d0b2ff5daba02998245d5c7e624f46bd2242a

commit_message:
Remove use of contextlib.nested

Removed use of contextlib.nested call from codebase, as it has been
deprecated since Python 2.7.

There are also known issues with contextlib.nested that were addressed
by the native support for multiple "with" variables. For instance, if
the first object is created but the second one throws an exception,
the first object's __exit__ is never called. For more information see
https://docs.python.org/2/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.nested
contextlib.nested is also not compatible with Python 3.

Multi-patch set for easier chunks. This one addresses the
neutron/tests/unit/agent/test_securitygroups_rpc.py tests.

Line continuation markers (e.g. '\') had to be used or syntax
errors were thrown. While using parentheses is the preferred way
for multiple line statements, but in case of long with statements
backslashes are acceptable.

Partial-Bug: 1428424
Change-Id: Ia66b98423b14fc7d1bbf6d8a673a49f798d328fa

do that. In some environment (for example, when building the package
under Jenkins), writing on $HOME is simply not allowed, and Glanceclient
can simply ignore it. This patch allows the mkdir() to fail, which fixes

commit_message:
Do not crash on homedir mkdir

Glanceclient is trying to create ~/.glanceclient, and crashes if it can't
do that. In some environment (for example, when building the package
under Jenkins), writing on $HOME is simply not allowed, and Glanceclient
can simply ignore it. This patch allows the mkdir() to fail, which fixes
the issue.

Closes-Bug: #1446096
Change-Id: Ib3591fb4e54ccd2fe63a1a4815551ac10ef5b961
(cherry picked from commit 1686d6aa535562ae2ea6e04b6dfd59b86c998c8a)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-27 16:00:10.000000000', 'message': "Wire in optional network creation for overcloud

This patch enables uses to selectively enable the creation
of split out networks for the overcloud traffic. These
networks will be created on the undercloud's neutron
instance.

By default a noop network is used so that no extra networks
are created. This allows our default to continue being
all traffic on the control plane.

Change-Id: Ied49d9458c2d94e9d8e7d760d5b2d971c7c7ed2d

commit_message:
Wire in optional network creation for overcloud

This patch enables uses to selectively enable the creation
of split out networks for the overcloud traffic. These
networks will be created on the undercloud's neutron
instance.

By default a noop network is used so that no extra networks
are created. This allows our default to continue being
all traffic on the control plane.

Change-Id: Ied49d9458c2d94e9d8e7d760d5b2d971c7c7ed2d

commit_message:
Fix remove_disabled_extensions to remove an extension at the last position

remove_disabled_extensions do matching by '$ext_to_remove","'. So it doesn't
match an extension at the last position in extensions_list.
This patch fixes that.

Closes-Bug: #1443254
Change-Id: I194b483de797697ba06b320cf33f1bac67fc0cc7

commit_message:
Added a validation to the Keypair creation form

In nova, the keypair manes are unique for each user. The form will
validate that the name is already used in the list of existing keypairs.

Closes-Bug: 1456657
Change-Id: I223c963349fe65ca09ed805edeebbe234c0131dc

commit_message:
Empty cell should obey sorting order

Currently any empty cell will be sorted to the bottom, regardless it is
asc or desc sort. This patchset is to change the sorting default behavior of
the jquery tablesorter such that empty cells should obey sorting.

Change-Id: Ib290c3bc4ab9c1b4e2bb0e4d4f6751615308f0b5
Closes-Bug: #1432904

Typically we encourage groups to put testing in the projcet being tested. Makes life easier in a multitude of ways (though features like depends-on are helping fix the problems in that space). Just to confirm you want a new repo that will have to managed in sync with rally to do CI instead of just having rally carry the scripts it needs?'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2015-03-23 23:21:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Clark,

This project is not just bunch of scripts that are required for testing Rally...

The idea is to make it simple to use Rally as Third Party CI, so you can just run rally-ci deamon on hardware that you have and you'll get ready for usage Third Party CI.

There are few reasons where we such jobs can be used: 

  - Performance/Regression/Scale/Volume testing of specific drivers on specific hardware against every patch

  - Historical performance data - like we are running test against the same hardware -> we can get good enough results to make trending

  - If somebody would like to use Rally instead of Tempest for functional testing 

Rally-CI consumes Rally project as a Lib, so we were thinking quite a lot about merging it to Rally, but as a result we get quite different projects that should be in different repos. 

Makes sense?"}, {'account_id': 7369, 'date': '2015-03-24 10:31:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 11809, 'date': '2015-03-24 15:05:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-17 23:49:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add new rally-ci project

Third party CI for Rally project.

This project in future will be consumed in other projects
to run performance and scalability tests against upstream
patches on own hardware.

Change-Id: I83cbae033613fc231c5c9d3a9c92898b3afff76d

based on trust information.

commit_message:
Check delay and timeout when editing monitor

Validate delay and timeout when editing monitor, make sure delay
is greater than or equal to timeout. And add more detail in help
message for delay input.

Change-Id: I5dd16d385e85d282b5baba8b1bc0a6ed7d79ec26
Closes-bug: #1446997

[{'created': '2015-05-25 17:51:35.000000000', 'message': "IBP: Fix socket.timeout catching

Recent version of python-requests doesn't catch socket.timeout()
This patch resolves the issue by explicit adding socket.timeout to

Change-Id: Ifcadf9efbec633175bb1bd31cf7f58732c2e78c4
Closes-Bug: #1458526

commit_message:
IBP: Fix socket.timeout catching

Recent version of python-requests doesn't catch socket.timeout()
This patch resolves the issue by explicit adding socket.timeout to
the list of expected exceptions to be caught.

Change-Id: Ifcadf9efbec633175bb1bd31cf7f58732c2e78c4
Closes-Bug: #1458526

commit_message:
Do not set deploy_ramdisk and deploy_kernel as flavor keys

Setting deploy_ramdisk and deploy_kernel as flavor extra_specs is
deprecated from more than a cycle and not supported anymore. The deploy
kernel and ramdisk name are instead passed to register_nodes so that
they are set on the node itself in Ironic.

Co-authored-By: James Slagle <jslagle@redhat.com>
Co-authored-By: Derek Higgins <derekh@redhat.com>

Change-Id: I494e3579c3daad7bf13a8127cf83cc61f82f913a
Related-To: I0727126770e6c79c898560a34e91a10686696d82
Related-Bug: 1453076
Depends-On: Ie38d3186b45fe00e0577f4b0f8b6a971edb9827d

commit_message:
Add rabbit OCF functions to get pacemaker node names

W/o this fix, the failover time was longer than expected
as rabbit nodes was able to query corosync nodes left the
cluster and also try to join them by rabbit cluster ending
up being reset and rejoin alive nodes later.
1) Add functions:
  a) to get all alive nodes in the partition
  b) to get all nodes
This fixes get_monitor behaviour so that it ignores
attributes for dead nodes as crm_node behaviour
changed with upgrade of pacemaker. So rabbit nodes will
never try to join the dead ones.

2) Fix bash scopes for local variables
Minor change removing unexcpeted behavior when local variable
impacts global scope.

Related-bug: #1436812

Change-Id: I89b716b4cd007572bb6832365d4424669921f057
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Use assertIn instead of assertTrue in tests

Since `assertIn` is provided for checking if value exists in given
container, it is not formal to use `assertTrue` for it.

Change-Id: Ie1392839b5ca436957463bb29f2784d48cfcbf75

commit_message:
Clean up failed clones in VMAX driver

If the clone operation fails, clean up is not done properly in
the VMAX driver. This patch catches the exception during the
clone operation, removes the target volume, and then re-throw
the exception.

Closes-Bug: #1440154
Change-Id: I548d5da09cb66077f04b1c5f1aa168c5bd5cf02e

commit_message:
Initialize data field of cluster_policy after policy attaching

During the progress of policy attaching, some useful data could
be generated, e.g. ceilometer alarm ID for scaling policy, or lb
pool ID for lb policy. This patch allows attach method of policy
to return these data and then persist them using the data field of
cluster_policy object.

commit_message:
Register ibm-db-alembic import for DB2 migrations

This patch adds the optional runtime dependency to support db2
for alembic migration, will not break the default mysql path.

This is needed for the IBM DB2 third party CI to work on this
project.

Closes-Bug: 1442524

Change-Id: I9db112dbdc2d02df88ad676a6b21018f1d6f1724

- check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-large-ops http://logs.openstack.org/20/174220/2/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-large-ops/6a55121/ : SUCCESS in 27m 07s'}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-04-16 09:22:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Well yamamoto, because it's something urgent to fix (the other patch), and it was marked with +A and +2.

Anyway, the probability calculations indicate that:

with pre-this patch, the chances to have a 0.1% collision requires 590591155176472576 security groups,

with this patch 
2419061371602831671296 security groups

I believe the database will be long dead before we get into such amount of security groups, thus the risk is very low (thanks salvatore for pushing me a bit into perspective).

I don't want to delay the other patch either neither I think this one is super important, anyway having probability more at your side it's always better, I don't think it's objective at all in this case."}, {'account_id': 8655, 'date': '2015-04-16 13:47:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Miguel: If patch obtains +2 and +A and we know it contains a glitch then we should start thinking about the flow and how could it get such votes. I agree with Yamamoto and rather fix this in original patch even though it already got +2's."}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-04-16 13:51:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@jakub, as I said before, I don't want to block on the bugfix which fixes something more important on the gate.

This is just an enhancement. :)"}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-04-16 13:52:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

We could still use more of the uuid if we cutted down IPv4 / IPv6 to just 4/6, having a 

N4 / N6 prefix on the ipset groups.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-04-16 19:06:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

You could also just get rid of the N completely so the prefix is only a 4 or 6. While you're at it, strip out the '-' chars as well because they are a waste. 

Finally, translate the ID to use other letters of the alphabet. We are wasting at least an entire bit of storage for each char by only putting a hex character in there. That means you can pack 5 hex chars into 4 chars for the ipset name (assuming we are limited to alphanumeric case insensitive)."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-04-16 19:07:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Oh, looks like it's case sensitive and we can add in a few special chars so we can get 6 bits per char. That means the we can get a 3/2 packing ratio."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-04-16 19:08:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

See it seems like what is tolerable as a probability is completely arbitrary. If we are going to optimize it, we should spend the time to actually do it to the fullest extent possible.'}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-04-16 21:59:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

There is some usability component helping us on debug because it's a very easy mapping from sg-id to ipset.

But I agree with you, if we're to optimize, we can get rid of slashes, and all uneccesary info, but packing it more to break human trackability may be it's too much.


I only looked at this because a naming change is an opportunity to optimize it a bit.

As you said, we have a higher risk with ports. And by the way, not sure if we have a worst cut with iptable chain names, and that's always going to be hit first, so ... probably this patch is pointless.

I'll look at the chain naming tomorrow... 

Thanks for your patience Kevin! ;)"}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-04-17 19:10:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-04-17 19:16:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

ARgh, even my --no-rebase of a dependent updated this, but nothing has changed.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-04-17 19:24:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-04-17 19:25:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Reduce prefix and suffix length in ipsets

The new NET prefix introduced by I8177699b157cd3eac46e2f481f47b5d966c49b07
increases collision chances by trimming the sg_id by 3 more chars.

This patch reduces the prefix to 1 single char and also reduces the
swap suffix to reduce the chances of collision.

Change-Id: I8a1559e173a05b2297c5cd2efa9fee7627b88a4f
Related-Bug: #1439817
Related-Bug: #1444397

commit_message:
Ensure mac address added to iptables is always in unix format

When a allowed address pair entry is added with a mac format
other than unix format the ovs-vs agent keeps on restarting as
it is not able to save the proper iptables due to the error
"Error while processing VIF ports". This fix makes sure
that the mac address sent to the iptables firewall is always
in the unix format

Change-Id: I86bbf3cb2adf9b998190e472691c01d068ebab9c
Closes-Bug: #1457971

commit_message:
Add mode validation for cluster to PUT method

The original fix did not work for validation while updating the cluster
only with deployment mode, which is how the deployment mode is set via
python-fuelclient.

Change-Id: Id3dcbfd339db184ffe75ca8d06675195fe9486de
Closes-Bug: #1456540

commit_message:
Move 'verify_firewall' to a separate test case

'verify_firewall' shouldn't fail the test cases that use
prepare_ha_neutron/prepare_ha_nova as their dependence.

Change-Id: I5342753cdfcd34b1d768a50d8dc3421f5d34f9f3
Closes-Bug:#1458772

commit_message:
fix node-get-console returns url always start with http

When we specify terminal_cert_dir in /etc/ironic/ironic.conf,
ironic node-get-console returns console_info url which should
start with https; When we do not specify terminal_cert_dir in
/etc/ironic/ironic.conf, console_info url should start with http.

Change-Id: Ic837bd80d42b631f8ea4d2bac7b255f8e13affe3
Closes-Bug: 1458748

commit_message:
fixup! Typing error in unit test test_content_disposition

Typing error in unit test
The spec of Content-Disposition does not require a space character after
comma: http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2183.txt

Change-Id: Ica1eb47e3ae462653b59971e379d381cb444a86a
Related-Bug: 1458497

commit_message:
Disable meaningless sort keys in list command

The sort keys are:
For ports: 'extra'
For chassis: 'extra'
For nodes: 'properties', 'driver_info', 'extra',
           'instance_info', 'driver_internal_info'

Disable these sort keys in REST API.

Change-Id: I82d5674d14b4357d04f59187dd30ce8e848bd035
Partial-Bug: #1446146

commit_message:
Add flag to include hacking

Add a flag to allow the update script to update the hacking dependency
like any other, to make it easier to bulk-update projects with multiple
repositories.

Change-Id: I1edc795da86064360aaecf04856a9a9b1c97a2b1

(2 comments)

So there is clearly a bug in the clean up for these tests because addCleanup is always executed after tearDown. However you're proposed fix only covers the case where the tests passes.

Instead you should modify the tear down method to check the image in use and perform the rebuild when needed. That way it'll always leave the image in the known state after a test is run.

Alternatively, we could just break the image reuse here. split the rebuild tests out into a separate method which creates a new server for each test case. That will make the code much simpler to follow, but at the penalty of a few more operations being performed."}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-05-15 16:25:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-05-15 19:35:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2015-05-15 19:36:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

ServerActionsTestJSON.test_rebuild_server
ServerActionsTestJSON.test_rebuild_server_in_stop_state
ServerActionsTestJSON.test_resize_server_confirm

The count of failed tests will be more than 3 if we run tests in
parallel mode.

The root cause of this is wrong cleanup order in the test
"test_rebuild_server". In particular the issue is in these code lines:

    # If the server was rebuilt on a different image, restore it to the
    # original image once the test ends
    if self.image_ref_alt != self.image_ref:
        self.addCleanup(self.client.rebuild,
                        (self.server_id, self.image_ref))

For each test in file tempest/tempest/api/compute/
servers/test_server_actions.py we have the following tearDown():

    def tearDown(self):
        server = self.client.get_server(self.server_id)
        self.assertEqual(self.image_ref, server['image']['id'])
        self.server_check_teardown()
        super(ServerActionsTestJSON, self).tearDown()

But addCleanup() is called after "tearDown" methods. Thus we rebuild
server after tearDown() but we should do it before.

Change-Id: I3a743f55fa223e234b3c49d1191af0b627697b74
Closes-Bug: #1454755

commit_message:
Fixing wrong cleanup order in test "test_rebuild_server"

Some tests (see the list below) from file tempest/tempest/api/compute/
servers/test_server_actions.py will not work if we specify different IDs
of images for options "image_ref" and "image_ref_alt".

Here is these tests:
ServerActionsTestJSON.test_rebuild_server
ServerActionsTestJSON.test_rebuild_server_in_stop_state
ServerActionsTestJSON.test_resize_server_confirm

The root cause of this is wrong cleanup order in the test
"test_rebuild_server". In particular the issue is in these code lines:

    # If the server was rebuilt on a different image, restore it to the
    # original image once the test ends
    if self.image_ref_alt != self.image_ref:
        self.addCleanup(self.client.rebuild,
                        (self.server_id, self.image_ref))

For each test in file tempest/tempest/api/compute/
servers/test_server_actions.py we have the following tearDown():

    def tearDown(self):
        server = self.client.get_server(self.server_id)
        self.assertEqual(self.image_ref, server['image']['id'])
        self.server_check_teardown()
        super(ServerActionsTestJSON, self).tearDown()

But addCleanup() is called after "tearDown" methods.

We can move code lines that check the server was rebuilt to addCleanup()
and invoke this check only in those tests that are related to rebuilding
the server.

Closes-Bug: #1454755

Change-Id: I3a743f55fa223e234b3c49d1191af0b627697b74

commit_message:
VBox - there are a lot of ssh.exe processes under Cygwin

When we execute the installation of the Fuel master node we are
launching ssh commands and checking messages in the file
bootstrap_admin_node.log. If the ssh processes accumulate in the
operating system you could see the following error: “The system
has no more ptys”.
Also Cygwin does not work correctly with the command
"send "res=$(for i in 1 2 3 4...)"

Change-Id: I30aab51452505e88c18abc866f88efde2d7650fb
Closes-Bug: #1457956

commit_message:
Do not add auth token in context for noauth API mode

Client can send auth token even if API works in "noauth" mode.
This behavior misinforms conductor service. Now if context
received via RPC do not contains auth token API works w/o
authentication.

Change-Id: I67f0d3dcbfa80916ae3e77d03f6cc91244ca2179

commit_message:
Add release notes to docs for past few releases

This commit adds release notes to the tempest-lib docs for the past 3
releases. This was overlooked for 0.4.0 and 0.3.0, so those were
included along with the recent 0.5.0 release.

commit_message:
Delete neutron ports when the node cleaning fails

Neutron ports are not getting deleted when the node is set to clean
failed state. This commit is to delete the neutron ports even when the
node cleaning fails.

Change-Id: I1f41e774fdf100f9da0859e6a2af48df8ab9917f
Closes-Bug:#1449581

commit_message:
Don't create empty quota set requests

The way that getattr is called with the None default you will always
create a compute_kwargs dictionary with key: None values. This means
that we will always send these empty requests to the servers.

Change so that only actually changed values end up in the quota set
requests and get sent.

This cherry-pick involves part of two patches as part of the bug was
addressed by an otherwise unrelated patch.

Change-Id: I33bc3f4e1a8013ec672e995648d27513064baf26
Closes-Bug: #1451640
(cherry picked from commit 179ed18c30cea438e13ba92997d3f671e5f76a84 and
commit 911efe8fd5d7026928394e848bc410abd08c3e4d)

commit_message:
[install-guide] Keystone updates

Update the keystone content as follows:

1) Fix permissions issue with WSGI on RHEL/CentOS/Fedora.

2) Clarify note about disabling the keystone service with
   Apache and make it apply to all distributions.

3) Remove PKI configuration steps because the guide uses
   UUID tokens for all distributions.

4) Add workaround for location of keystone-paste.ini file on
   RHEL/CentOS/Fedora.

Change-Id: I9e3ec34be4956dd62f0f1dd9fa9b437d649e7413
Closes-Bug: #1454041
Closes-Bug: #1457850
Closes-Bug: #1454718
Implements: blueprint installguide-kilo

commit_message:
Make sure filtered_by_ip list servers test uses correct ip filter

The default tenants are now created with both ip4 and ip6 subnets. The order
in which they appear from a 'server show' is non-deterministic. This test
was just taking the first one and using 'ip' as the search parameter. For
an ipv6 subnet it needs to use 'ip6'. This test was only failing in the
non-isolated case because the tempest isolated tenant code uses only v4.

The ip6 case is now skipped due to nova bug 1450859 which causes the ip6
filter to always return all servers.

Change-Id: I242edb56bbfc9696d290c75c73918b93295efecf

commit_message:
Handle ports with no local VLAN entry correctly

db_get_val returns a list when there is no entry. The local
VLAN restoration code wasn't expecting that so it would result
in unhashable errors.

This fixes the issue by converting an empty list to None.

Closes-Bug: #1458712
Change-Id: I6c599bdccb1fc6a626d222541cef8dcfde0713da

commit_message:
Update pyremotevbox documentation

This commit updates the suggested version of
pyremotevbox to 0.5.0 which removes the requirement
to install a ZSI library separately. This is important
because some distributions don't have this packaged.

Change-Id: I59e2418a735830409891e84fcc048b4005241cad

Unorder compare in tests

On occassion the values from schema are presented in a different order.
Compare them in an unordered way as we only care that both are present.

commit_message:
Update hacking to fix pep8 failure

With the release of pbr 1.0.0, we need a newer version of hacking.
Update the version. hacking is manually synced from global
requirements repo, use the version from there.

See also
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/064362.html

Change-Id: Ic3ff9ad74acd57fe149e5873fefe8a99e1d701d8

commit_message:
Use session loading in cinder

Use the default session options in cinder. We then create an
authentication plugin that can be used with the session. This custom
plugin will be replaced later with one from the context.

Change-Id: I48babb4e2b0fc9f07a3a0088c3d31eabcc43905a

commit_message:
Add missing dependencies (from pip-missing-reqs)

Any explicit imports we have in magnum, we should specify
the pypi package version number in our requirements. The
pip-missing-reqs helps us find these.

Note that python-dateutil is an optional import in
the python-k8sclient AND it's not in the global requirements
so not adding that.

we are adding here:

commit_message:
Enable NeutronL3HA by default in Pacemaker scenario

WARNING: NeutronL3HA must not be enabled if ControllerCount=1 or the
deployment will error. It is safe to enable in CI where we deploy
HA scenario with ControllerCount=3 but having it in the enviroment
file means people might be tempted to pass this when using
ControllerCount=1 as well, considering it maybe a needed param.

Instack passes this paraparameter only when ControllerCont>=1 see [1].

1. https://github.com/rdo-management/instack-undercloud/blob/master/scripts/instack-deploy-overcloud#L367

Change-Id: Ia4dbd5e60cc5f7eac71721fb918fee3ca7e53105

commit_message:
Change IP to management_ip

* HAproxy doesn't listen to 35357 on public_ip. This change corrects ip
  in keystone_url for Rados Gateway

Change-Id: Ie443944534c026498880928f22cc14a7ed516716
Closes-Bug: 1446704

hi, gordon chung

I do have verified this, both by writing a small script and add a LOG.error to check if old auth_ref is same as new auth_ref. they both show that this is work.

As you mentioned the table is still increasing, so I check that table, and find that token table does increase, but only one in each interval, and finally I find out that the network.floatingip will call nova_client.Client() in every interval, that class will post a token every time

I'm sorry for missing that, it seems not only one place to deal with token problem

as you mentioned the key_ring, I checked the keystoneclient again, if I don't misunderstand it, that argument is using keystoneclient its own keyring, and auth_ref can enable us use our own strategy. both can work, but it seems use_keyring will be simpler 
see: 

* https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/blob/master/keystoneclient/httpclient.py#L245
* https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/blob/master/keystoneclient/httpclient.py#L299"}, {'account_id': 6676, 'date': '2014-04-16 09:06:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-16 09:06:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@gordon chung

I have test auth_ref and use_keyring in devstack master branch, both show that it works (there are no more post token after service init), and I test os_cache with novaclient which is based on keyring also(https://github.com/openstack/python-novaclient/blob/master/novaclient/client.py#L445). I remember keyring needs password too, but I don't know why it behaviors good in my local devstack environment.

Currently, ceilometer generate huge amount of tokens in a middle scale environment, although cron job of keystone-manage token_flush can clean expired token, but other service should not heavy that burden

and in some scenarios, the token is every large (around 10k?) according to the token format and endpoint count, then post a new token will cause more resource, so my workmate want the ceilometer to use token cache

I think an option is better than hardcode to use cache, so I will upload another patch to implement it"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-16 12:51:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Works for me

commit_message:
Reduce new token when call client object

When we create a keystoneclient object, we can use its own cache
functionality by set use_keyring to True. And also we can use cache
for novaclient by set os_cache to True. These improvements can reduce
the burden of token table in keystone.

Change-Id: I56d975e36cbf1da8ecf1df9fb83c342dfb45eb21
Closes-Bug: #1291136

commit_message:
Make lists query-able during fetching samples and meters

Query by list-element in resource_matedata works
ok only in SQL implementation. We need it in all of backends.
For this purpose we may use dict_to_keyval function to store
metadata in SQL and HBase - in these backends we store flattened
metadata as well as raw. For Mongo and DB2 we neeed only construct
correct query from user's input.
Added several tests.

This commit doesn't fix HBase issue: flattened metadata is not used during query processing.

Change-Id: I19e48b3890f096326eb830c5c7b5d2cd1eba251b

commit_message:
Evaluate alarms by their dependency order

Currently, we evaluator alarms in the order of their ids, which simply
ignore their dependency relationship. This patch introduces a way
to evaluate alarms according to the dependency chains.

Change-Id: Ie5c3ef5d11475cf64fdc944fd5e1b785aa9dfdc7
Closes-Bug: #1310500
Implements: blueprint resolve-combination-alarm-dependency-chain

Going to stand up a dev environment with this to test it'}, {'account_id': 11356, 'date': '2015-04-17 15:03:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I haven't actually tested it, but if a user runs without redirection, there will be no feedback on whether anything has happened?"}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-04-17 19:24:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

So I tried this out (much later in the day than I had hoped to) and this details what I saw: http://paste.openstack.org/show/204501/

When I redirect glance image-download with > I get a zero-length file. I think there's a problem in the conditional for the if. For example, see http://paste.openstack.org/show/204504/

In that case args.file will be None and isatty() will be False so we won't ever save the file. I think what you want to check is:

    if not sys.stdout.isatty() or args.file is not None:

Which can be rewritten to:

    if not (sys.stdout.isatty() and args.file is None):

Thanks Cindy!"}, {'account_id': 9096, 'date': '2015-04-17 21:09:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-04-17 21:18:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

I'm actually +2 on this, but I think Louis has valid concerns about the case where someone may be confused about nothing happening when they're neither redirecting nor using --file.

Perhaps we should add an "else" and tell the person that we expect them either redirect the output (with > or |) or to use --file.

In other words, we should probably document the expected use of:

    glance image-download IMAGE-ID > image.img
    glance image-download IMAGE-ID --file image.img'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-04-17 22:02:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I think users would appreciate a message rather than no output when specifying neither option.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-17 22:06:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Check image-download for redirection

Currently when you download an image without specifying
a file or redirecting the output, the image is dumped into
the console as gibberish. We can avoid this if we
check if file is being redirected or if a file is specified.

Change-Id: I257760752f05b82b935cf19fb10573ee7ff1395d

commit_message:
Open development for 2015.2.1

This matches the workflow of other projects like neutron
and should fix the following pbr-semver errors.

2015-05-20 23:29:28.302 |     ValueError: git history requires a target version of pbr.version.SemanticVersion(2015.1.2), but target version is pbr.version.SemanticVersion(2015.1.1)

Change-Id: Iad18695e5ce9f8a4d28708a4b214612fbb31134b

commit_message:
Revert fix that issues Unauthorized exception

This reverts the fix to properly issue an Unauthorized
exception [1] because it was a workaround, and the proper fix
was made in oslo.incubator [2] and has been sync'd [3].

[1] I930fd61a896f62a2984cca1e4d40e5d89644aa3f
[2] I3b9a20174da482f570d02319e68f46dcaa10ca9c
[3] Iab799c8209872e2faa9ec6d33a426347b6478cce

Change-Id: Ia3f5695f73bfff19a9f24117fa881e8d9ed039d3
Closes-Bug: #1402840

commit_message:
Don't swallow AssertionErrors

Most validation errors are in fact the user's problem, but in the case of
an AssertionError that's a real problem with Heat. We should return 500
status codes and log the tracebacks, not wrap the in validation exceptions.

Change-Id: I71d91a5413d7f026b332014487583b7f2762b322
